<BLOCK1><TI>STATEMENT OF DEFENCE OF THE DEFENDANT <UNDER>LENGARA VENTURES INC. (the &ldquo;Defendant&rdquo;)</UNDER></TI>
<P>1. The Defendant denies each and every allegation in the Statement of Claim unless expressly admitted herein. For reference purposes only, the Defendant adopts the defined terms as set out in the Statement of Claim.</P>
<P>2. The Defendant admits the allegations of fact contained in paragraphs 1, 2, 3 and 10 of the Statement of Claim.</P>
<P>3. In answer to paragraph 4, the Defendant admits that the Plaintiff and the Defendant executed a contract in writing dated March 12, 2009, which was drafted by the Plaintiff (the &ldquo;Original Contract&rdquo;).</P>
<P>4. In further answer to paragraph 4, pursuant to the Contract, the Plaintiff agreed to provide more than project management services to the Improvement. The services to be provided by the Plaintiff to the Defendant included provision of labour, materials, and other services to the Improvement by the Plaintiff and by the sub-contractors to the Plaintiff.</P>
<P>5. The terms of the Original Contract in respect of services to be provided by the Plaintiff to the Improvement, were from time to time amended by further agreements between the Plaintiff and the Defendant made between March 12, 2009 and December 26, 2009 (collectively referred to as the &ldquo;Contract&rdquo;).</P>
<P>6. Among the changes to the Original Contract after March 12, 2009, the fees for labour to be provided by the Plaintiff to the construction of the Improvement were reduced from the amounts provided by the Original Contract.</P>
<P>7. On December 26, 2009, the Plaintiff and the Defendant agreed, among other matters, as a term of the Contract, that the Plaintiff was required to provide a statutory declaration to the Defendant in respect of the invoices issued by the Plaintiff to the Defendant upon substantial completion of the Improvement, prior to payment of those invoices by the Defendant.</P>
<P>8. On December 26, 2009, the Plaintiff agreed with the Defendant that, except for circumstances beyond the Plaintiffs control, the Improvement was to be substantially completed by January 25, 2010, such that the building on the Lands was then to be completed and ready for occupancy.</P>
<P>9. It was an express, or alternatively an implied term of the Contract, that the Statutory Declaration to be provided by the Defendant was to be provided prior to payment of the invoices issued by the Plaintiff for services to the Improvement upon substantial completion, such that the Defendant was to have received assurances that all accounts for services to the Improvement incurred by the Plaintiff, for which the Defendant might in any way be held responsible, had been paid in full.</P>
<P>10. On or about January 15, 2010, the Defendant paid all amounts then due to the Plaintiff pursuant to the Contract for services to the Improvement (the &ldquo;Progress Payment&rdquo;).</P>
<P>11. After the Progess Payment of January 15, 2010, the Plaintiff issued three further invoices for services provided by the Plaintiff to the Improvement, pursuant to the Contract. The invoices were dated February 2, 2010, March 9, 2010, and March 9, 2010, respectively. The total of the amounts invoiced by the Plaintiff to the Defendant pursuant to the three invoices was the sum of $104,648.91 (collectively the &ldquo;Invoices&rdquo;).</P>
<P>12. At all relevant times, the principal of the Plaintiff and the operating mind behind the operations of the Plaintiff was Alfredo Hermano.</P>
<P>13. A temporary Occupancy Permit was issued by the City of Vancouver in respect of the building on the Lands on March 1, 2010.</P>
<P>14. In accordance with the terms of the Contract, Alfredo Hermano duly executed a statutory declaration dated the 24<SUP>th</SUP>of February, 2010, which was subsequently provided to the Defendant in accordance with the terms of the Contract in conjunction with a request for payment of the three Invoices totaling $104,648.91.</P>
<P>15. The statutory declaration deposed by Alfredo Hermano contained, inter alia, the following declaration:
<QUOTE><P><EM>that all accounts for labour, subcontracts, products, services, and construction machinery and equipment which have been incurred directly by the Contractor in the performance of the work as required by the Contract, and for which the Owner might in any way be held responsible, have been paid in full as required by the Contract up to and including the latest progress payment received, as identified above, except for</EM>:
<P1><EM>1) holdback monies properly retained</EM>,</P1>
<P1><EM>2) payments deferred by agreement, or</EM></P1>
<P1><EM>3) amounts withheld by reason of legitimate dispute which have been identified to the party or parties, from whom payment has been withheld</EM>.</P1></P></QUOTE>
<P1>(the &ldquo;Declaration&rdquo;)</P1></P>
<P>16. The Declaration was false. On the date the Declaration was made and when it was provided to the Defendant there were, to the knowledge of the Plaintiff and of Alfredo Hermano, four subcontractors to the Plaintiff who had issued invoices to the Plaintiff for services to the Improvement prior to the latest Progress Payment, which invoices were not then paid, and for which the Defendant could be held responsible. The unpaid amounts to these subcontractors then totaled approximately $75,000.00 (the &ldquo;Unpaid SubContracts).</P>
<P>17. The said Alfredo Hermano knew that the Declaration was false when it was made by him and when he provided it to the Defendant in conjunction with the request for payment. The false Declaration was made and was provided in order to mislead the Defendant in order to induce it to pay the Invoices notwithstanding the fact that there were then the significant Unpaid Sub-Contracts.</P>
<P>18. After the request was made for payment of the Invoices, and the Declaration was provided to the Defendant in support of the request, the Defendant did not pay the Invoices because it had then become aware of the Unpaid Sub-Contracts.</P>
<P>19. Upon becoming aware of the Unpaid Sub-Contracts the Defendant advised the Plaintiff that it was prepared to pay all amounts then properly due pursuant to the Contract subject to satisfactory arrangements for payment of the Unpaid Sub- Contracts. Notwithstanding this, the Plaintiff and its principal, Alfredo Hermano, refused to make arrangements to pay the Unpaid Sub-Contracts and caused the claim of lien which is the subject of these proceedings to be filed against the Lands thereby claiming the amount of $399,417.36 (the &ldquo;Claim of Lien&rdquo;).</P>
<P>20. The Claim of Lien was, to the knowledge of the Plaintiff and the said Alfredo Hermano, false.</P>
<P>21. Prior to the filing of the Lien the Plaintiff had issued invoices under the Contract for services which had already been paid for by the Defendant or for items which were not properly chargeable to the Defendant pursuant to the Contract (the &ldquo;Duplication&rdquo;). The Duplication was in the total sum of $18,131.50. The Duplication on the prior invoices issued by the Plaintiff was discovered by the Defendant in or about January of 2010, and an accounting of the Duplication was provided to the Plaintiff, who has refused or neglected to respond to the same.</P>
<P>22. In further answer to paragraphs 5 and 6:
<P1>a) The Plaintiff invoiced the Defendant pursuant to the Contract for services to the Improvement to the date March 9, 2010;</P1>
<P1>b) When the Lien was filed the only unpaid invoices of the Plaintiff were the three Invoices dated February 2, 2010, March 9, 2010 and March 9, 2010 respectively, totaling $104,684.91;</P1>
<P1>c) No invoice was ever issued by the Defendant to the Plaintiff for the sum of $399,417.36 now claimed, prior to the filing of the Claim of Lien;</P1>
<P1>d) No demand was ever made by the Plaintiff to the Defendant for payment of the sum of $399,417.36 now claimed, until after the filing of the Claim of Lien.</P1></P>
<P>23. Prior to receipt of the Invoices and the Declaration the Defendant had paid to the Plaintiff all amounts due pursuant to the Unpaid Sub-Contracts. Such payment was made to the Plaintiff on the condition that all of the amounts due to the Unpaid Sub-Contracts were to be paid from the funds paid to the Plaintiff. This was an express or alternatively an implied term of the Contract.</P>
<P>24. The Plaintiff has refused or neglected to pay the Unpaid Sub-Contracts to date.</P>
<P>25. The amount properly due to the Plaintiff under its Contract as at the date of the last Invoice properly issued, was the sum of $104,684.91, less the Duplication amounts invoiced of $18,131.50, less the amounts due on the Unpaid Sub- Contracts referred to herein.</P>
<P>WHEREFORE the Defendant submits that the action be dismissed with costs.</P>
<P>Dated: May 17, 2010</P>
<P>&ellip35; Solicitor for the Defendant, Lengara Ventures Inc.</P>
<P>This Statement of Defence is filed by Bruce Rosberg of the firm of Rosberg Sawatzky LLP, whose place of business and address for delivery is: #201-20353 64<SUP>th</SUP> Avenue, Langley, B.C. V2Y 1N5.</P></BLOCK1>
