<BLOCK1><TI>NOTICE OF APPLICATION</TI>
<P>Name of Applicant: Lengara Ventures Inc.</P>
<P><BOLD>TO: The Plaintiff and its Solicitor</BOLD></P>
<P><BOLD>TO: Alfredo Hermano</BOLD></P>
<P>TAKE NOTICE that an application will be made by the applicant to the presiding judge or master at the courthouse at Vancouver on July 6, 2012 at 9:45 a.m. for the orders set out in Part 1 below.</P>
<BLOCK2 LABEL="Part"><N>1:</N><TI>ORDERS SOUGHT</TI>
<P>1. The Defendant, Lengara Ventures Inc., is granted leave to file the Counterclaim and the Third Party Notice attached as Schedule &ldquo;A&rdquo; and Schedule &ldquo;B&rdquo; to this Notice of Application and the filed Counterclaim and Third Party Notice shall be served on the Plaintiff and the Third Party, Alfredo Hermano, within seven (7) days of receipt of same by the Defendant.</P>
<P>2. The Plaintiff, NGC Management Ltd., and Alfredo Hermano post security for costs in the amount of $50,000 and this action be stayed until security is posted.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2 LABEL="Part"><N>2:</N><TI>FACTUAL BASIS</TI>
<P>1. The Defendant Lengara Ventures Inc. owns lands and premises located at 3410 Lougheed Hwy, Vancouver, BC, presently legally described as Lot 1 Block 1 Section 38 Town of Hastings Suburban Lands Plan BCP43119 (the &ldquo;Lands&rdquo;).</P>
<P>2. The Plaintiff NGC Management Ltd (&ldquo;NGC&rdquo;) agreed with the Defendant to provide services for the management of the construction of a commercial building and related improvements to the Lands (collectively the &ldquo;Improvement&rdquo;).</P>
<P>3. The operating mind behind the operations of NGC was at all relevant times Alfredo Hermano.</P>
<P>4. On or about January 15, 2010, pursuant to an agreement between the parties, the Defendant paid invoices issued to date by NGC, for services rendered to date in connection with the Improvement (the &ldquo;Progress Payment&rdquo;).</P>
<P>5. The Improvement was to be completed by January 25, 2010, and the Plaintiff was to provide a statutory declaration to the Defendant upon substantial completion of the Improvement.</P>
<P>6. After the Progress Payment, Mr. Hermano provided the Defendant with a Statutory Declaration, dated the 24<SUP>th</SUP> of February, 2010, in conjunction with a request for payment of invoices totaling $104,648.91 (the &ldquo;Invoices&rdquo;).</P>
<P>7. The Statutory Declaration included the following declaration:
<QUOTE><P><EM>that all accounts for labour, subcontracts, products, services, and construction machinery and equipment which have been incurred directly by the Contractor in the performance of the work as required by the Contract, and for which the Owner might in any way be held responsible, have been paid in full as required by the Contract up to and including the latest progress payment received, as identified above, except for</EM>:</P>
<P><EM>1) holdback monies properly retained</EM>,</P>
<P><EM>2) payments deferred by agreement, or</EM></P>
<P><EM>3) amounts withheld by reason of legitimate dispute which have been identified to the party or parties, from whom payment has been withheld</EM>.</P>
<P>(the &ldquo;Declaration&rdquo;)</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>8. The Declaration made by Mr. Hermano was false. On the date the Declaration was made and on the date it was provided to the Defendant there were at least two subcontractors to the Plaintiff who had issued invoices for services to the Improvement prior to the Progress Payment, which invoices were not then paid, and for which the Defendant could be held responsible. The unpaid amounts to these two subcontractors then totaled $75,332.01 (the &ldquo;Unpaid Sub-Contracts&rdquo;).</P>
<P>9. As a result of the false declaration, the Defendant refused to pay the Invoices presented by the Plaintiff, without satisfactory arrangements being made for payment of the Unpaid Sub-Contracts.</P>
<P>21. Examinations for discovery have not been conducted. Trial of this matter was unilaterally reset for 5 days in June 2013.</P>
<P>22. The Plaintiff is a company incorporated pursuant to the laws of British Columbia. It is not in good standing, is named as a defendant in multiple legal proceedings, commenced in the BC Provincial Court (Small Claims Court) and BC Supreme Court, and does not have assets or property that would secure an order for costs.</P>
<P>23. Mr. Hermano is also named as a defendant in multiple legal proceedings commenced in the BC Provincial Court (Small Claims Court) and Supreme Court, and does not have any assets or property that would secure an order for costs.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2 LABEL="Part"><N>3:</N><TI>LEGAL BASIS</TI>
<BLOCK3><TI><UNDER>Extend Time to File Counterclaim and Third Party Notice</UNDER></TI>
<P>1. Rule 22-4(2) grants discretion to the court to extend any time period provided for in the <EM>Supreme Court Civil Rules</EM>.</P>
<P>2. The following factors have been considered to determine whether it is just and convenient to extend time to permit a counterclaim to be filed:
<P1>a) what was the length of the delay between receiving the statement of claim and proposing the draft counterclaim;</P1>
<P1>b) what were the reasons for delay;</P1>
<P1>c) whether the counterclaim would be time barred but for s. 4(1) of the <EM>Limitation Act</EM>;</P1>
<P1>d) the connection between the proposed counterclaim and the claim;</P1>
<P1>e) whether there will be prejudice to the defendant, such as would arise if denial of the application to file a counterclaim would prevent the defendant from making full answer and defence to the claim brought against it; and</P1>
<P1>f) whether there will be prejudice to the plaintiff by permitting the proposed counterclaim, such as if the counterclaim would require additional investigation and potentially delay the trial of the matter.</P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Smith v. British Columbia</SOC><CITE>2010 BCSC 928</CITE></CASEREF> (CanLII) citing <CASEREF><SOC>Squamish Indian Band v. Canadian Pacific Ltd.</SOC><CITE>[1998] BCJ No. 1726</CITE><COURTJUR>SC</COURTJUR></CASEREF></P1></P>
<P>3. Any delay in filing the proposed Counterclaim and Third Party Notice is not prejudicial to the Plaintiff.</P>
<P>10. The Plaintiff and Mr. Hermano, refused to make arrangements to pay the Unpaid SubContracts and NGC caused a lien to be filed against the Lands, claiming the amount of $399,417.36 for services allegedly provided to the Improvement on the Lands (the &ldquo;NGC Lien&rdquo;).</P>
<P>11. No invoice for the amount claimed pursuant to the NGC Lien was received by the Defendant prior to the filing of the NGC Lien.</P>
<P>12. The Unpaid Sub-Contracts were the subject of claims of lien filed against the Lands. The Defendant paid the sums claimed in the amounts of $21,727.03, and $57,648.11; NGC authorized such payment on account of its contract with each of those subcontractors and agreed that such amounts were to be deducted from the amount to be secured in respect of the Plaintiff's claim of lien.</P>
<P>13. The Plaintiff commenced its lawsuit on April 19, 2010. The Defendant filed its Statement of Defence on May 17, 2010. Notice of Trial was filed on June 30, 2010, setting the trial for not more than 10 days commencing on June 6, 2011.</P>
<P>14. The parties agreed in the summer of 2010 to refer the matter to either mediation or a Trial Management Conference in an effort to resolve their claims. A Judicial Settlement Conference was scheduled for April 8, 2011.</P>
<P>15. Until August 2010, the Defendant was engaged in the process of having liens filed against the Lands, including the NGC Lien, discharged.</P>
<P>16. As a result of the liens filed against the Lands, including the NGC Lien, the Defendant incurred costs and loss, including the loss of an anchor tenant, which loss was not known to be significant until early 2011 when the Defendant was unable to secure any tenant for the space the anchor tenant was to lease.</P>
<P>17. The Defendant provided to the Plaintiff a copy of a Counterclaim and Third Party Notice it intended to file mid-February 2011. The Plaintiff would not consent to the filing of the same, and the Defendant prepared an application for the same.</P>
<P>18. In April 2011, the Defendant was notified that the Plaintiff had filed a Notice of Intention to make a proposal pursuant to Division 1 of the <EM>Bankruptcy and Insolvency Act</EM>.</P>
<P>19. As a result of the Notice of Intention filed by the Plaintiff, the trial, a Judicial Settlement Conference, and a Trial Management Conference, set in these proceedings, were all adjourned by consent, and the Defendant making an application to extend the time to file its proposed Counterclaim and Third Party Notice was put on hold pending the Plaintiff proceeding with the claim herein.</P>
<P>20. At the end of November and in December 2011, the Defendant was informed the Plaintiff intended to proceed with its claim.</P>
<P>4. The proposed Counterclaim and Third Party Notice involve many issues of fact similar to the claim; the issues raised and relief sought are related to and connected with the subject matter of these proceedings.</P>
<P>5. The participation of Mr. Hermano in these proceedings is necessary to ensure that all matters in the proceeding may be effectually adjudicated on. The avoidance of multiple proceedings is fundamental to our rules of civil procedure.</P>
<P>6. In all the circumstances, it is just and convenient to permit the defendant to proceed with the proposed Counterclaim and Third Party Notice.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI><UNDER>Application for Security For Costs</UNDER></TI>
<P>7. The Court has inherent jurisdiction with respect to ordering security for costs, and will act in light of all the relevant circumstances.</P>
<P>8. The Court also derives authority from s. 236 of the <EM>Business Corporations Act</EM>, RSBC 2002 c. 57, to require security for costs, and stay a proceeding until the security is given, where a corporation is a plaintiff in a proceeding and it appears that the corporation will be unable to pay a successful defendants' costs.</P>
<P>9. The power to order security for costs against an individual is to be exercised cautiously, sparingly, and only under special or egregious circumstances.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Wang v. British Columbia Medical Association</SOC><CITE>2011 BCSC 1659</CITE></CASEREF> (CanLII) citing Dhillon J. in <CASEREF><SOC>Han v. Cho</SOC><CITE>2008 BCSC 1229</CITE></CASEREF></P1></P>
<P>10. The governing principles for awarding security for costs against a corporate plaintiff, and in considering whether egregious circumstances exist, are:
<P1>a) The court has complete discretion whether to order security, and will act in light of all the relevant circumstances.</P1>
<P1>b) The possibility or probability that the plaintiff company will be deterred from pursuing its claim is not, without more, sufficient reason for not ordering security.</P1>
<P1>c) The court must attempt to balance the injustices arising from use of security as an instrument of oppression to stifle a legitimate claim on the one hand, and use of impecuniosity as a means of putting unfair pressure on a defendant on the other;</P1>
<P1>d) The court may have regard to the merits of the action, but should avoid going into detail on the merits unless success of failure appears obvious;</P1>
<P1>e) The court can order any amount of security up to the full amount claimed as long as the amount is more than nominal;</P1>
<P1>f) Before the court refuses to order security on the ground that it would unfairly stifle a valid claim, the court must be satisfied that, in all the circumstances, it is probable that the claim would be stifled; and</P1>
<P1>g) The lateness of the application for security is a circumstance which can properly be taken into account.</P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>G.A.P. Contracting Ltd. v. 0790643 B.C. Ltd.</SOC><CITE>2011 BCSC 1059</CITE></CASEREF> (CanLII) citing <CASEREF><SOC>Kropp v. Swaneset Bay Golf Course</SOC><CITE>1977 CanLII 4037</CITE><COURTJUR>BCCA</COURTJUR></CASEREF></P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Wang v. British Columbia Medical Association</SOC><CITE>2011 BCSC 1659</CITE></CASEREF> (CanLII)</P1></P>
<P>11. In order to satisfy the test, a defendant has the obligation to demonstrate on a <EM>prima facie</EM> basis that the plaintiff would be unable to pay the defendant's costs in the event the plaintiffs action was to fail. If the defendant satisfies this first hurdle, the plaintiff may still avoid an order for security for costs by showing that it has sufficient exigible assets to satisfy any potential award of costs.</P>
<P>12. The public sources of information searched for evidence of exigible assets, corporate, Personal Property Registry, Land Title and court registry searches, revealed that the Plaintiff:
<P1>a) is not in good standing;</P1>
<P1>b) its sole officer and director is Mr. Hermano;</P1>
<P1>c) has no registered assets;</P1>
<P1>d) has outstanding claims against it; and</P1>
<P1>e) filed a Proposal pursuant to Division I of Part III of the <EM>Bankruptcy and Insolvency Act</EM>, which was approved by the Court in September 2011.</P1></P>
<P>13. The public sources of information searched for evidence of exigible assets, corporate, Personal Property Registry, Land Title and court registry searches, revealed that Mr. Hermano is:
<P1>a) the registered owner in fee simple (joint tenant) of lands legally described as Strata Lot XXXXXXXXXX District Lot XXXXXXXXXX Group XXXXXXXXXX New Westminster District Strata Plan XXXXXXXXXX, charged with a mortgage, and judgment as to the interests of Mr. Hermano</P1>
<P1>b) the defendant in proceedings commenced in both the Provincial (Small Claims) Court and Supreme Court of British Columbia, with claims against him for breach of trust, in the total amount of $200,487.77.</P1></P>
<P>14. In all the circumstances, an order for security for costs against both the plaintiff and Mr. Hermano is warranted.</P></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
