<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="I">AFFIDAVIT</TI>
<P>I, Bruce Rosberg, Lawyer, of #201, 20353 - 64<SUP>th</SUP> Avenue, in the Township of Langley, in the Province of British Columbia, make oath and say that:</P>
<P>1. I am counsel for the Defendant herein and as such have personal knowledge of the facts and matters hereinafter deposed to save and except where stated to upon information and belief and where so stated I verily believe them to be true.</P>
<P>2. I was consulted as counsel for the Defendant, from time to time, by Gary Walker for the Defendant, and by Alfredo Hermano, during the construction of, and in connection with, the commercial building and related improvements to the lands, described more particularly in the affidavit of Gary Walker sworn March 5, 2012.</P>
<P>3. The Plaintiff, NGC Management Ltd. (&ldquo;NGC&rdquo;) commenced these proceedings by Writ and Statement of Claim filed April 19, 2010. The Defendant filed its Statement of Defence on May 17, 2010. Notice of Trial setting down the trial of this proceeding, for not more than 10 days commencing June 6, 2011, was filed by the solicitors for the Plaintiff on June 30, 2010.</P>
<P>4. The amount secured herein in respect of the claim of lien filed by NGC is less than that claimed by NGC in its Claim of Lien; NGC authorized payment of two unpaid subcontractors who had filed claims of liens against the subject lands claiming through NGC: $21,227.03 was paid to counsel for 4361814 Canada Inc., successor in interest to Rona Revy Inc., and $54,104.98 was paid to counsel for Harrigan Rentals &amp; Equipment, who were subcontractors to NCG and who had claimed through NGC.</P>
<P>5. In the summer of 2010, the parties, through me and Daniel Le Dressay, counsel for NGC, agreed to refer the matters between our respective clients to either mediation or a Trial Management Conference, in an effort to resolve their claims. In October 2010, Mr. Le Dressay requisitioned the setting down of a judicial Settlement Conference for February 14, 2011, later rescheduled to April 8, 2011.</P>
<P>6. By letter dated February 15, 2011, I provided Mr, Le Dressay with a Counterclaim and Third Party Notice the Defendant intended to file. By email sent February 16, 2011, Mr. Le Dressay advised that he would not consent to the filing of the proposed pleadings.</P>
<P>7. Mr. Le Dressay advised me by email sent April 5, 2011, and in a telephone discussion on April 6, 2011, that NGC had filed a Notice of Intention to make a proposal pursuant to Division 1 of the <EM>Bankruptcy and Insolvency Act</EM>.</P>
<P>8. The trial, Judicial Settlement Conference, and Trial Management Conference were adjourned subsequent to Mr. Le Dressay's advice regarding the bankruptcy proposal, by consent, and the making of an application to extend the time for the Defendant to file its Counterclaim and Third Party Notice was put on hold pending the Plaintiff proceeding with these proceedings. Attached hereto collectively as Exhibit &ldquo;A&rdquo; is a copy of the April 5, 2011, email from Mr. Le Dressay referred to in the preceding paragraph and my letter to Mr. Le Dressay dated April 11, 2011, confirming the foregoing.</P>
<P>9. My office received communications from the office of Mr. Le Dressay at the end of November seeking to reset the trial. I spoke with Mr. Le Dressay in December and he confirmed that NGC had dealt with certain bankruptcy issues and that it intended to proceed with its claims herein.</P>
<P>10. Lists of Documents have been exchanged, but examinations for discovery have not been conducted, I believe further lists will be exchanged.</P>
<P>11. The trial was unilaterally reset at the end of March 2012 by the office of counsel for NGC for 5 days in June 2013. Further to a telephone conversation I had with Mr. Le Dressay, it is my understanding that the trial will be reset for 10 days.</P>
<P>12. NGC is a company incorporated pursuant to the laws of the Province of British Columbia. Searches of public registries have been conducted and based on the results of those searches, I verily believe that NGC is not in good standing and does not have any assets or property to secure an order for costs. Attached and marked as:
<P1>a) Exhibit &ldquo;B&rdquo; is a true copy of a BC Company Summary showing that:
<P2>i) NGC is a British Columbia company; and</P2>
<P2>ii) Mr. Hermano is the sole director and officer of NGC.</P2></P1>
<P1>b) Exhibit &ldquo;C&rdquo; is a true copy of Corporate Information for NGC showing that the company is not in good standing.</P1>
<P1>c) Exhibit &ldquo;D&rdquo; is a true copy of B.C. Land Title Search Results indicating that NGC is not the registered owner of any real property in British Columbia;</P1>
<P1>d) Exhibit &ldquo;E&rdquo; is a true copy of a BC Personal Property Registry Search indicating that NGC is not the registered owner of any personal property in British Columbia;</P1>
<P1>e) Exhibit &ldquo;F&rdquo; is a true copy of a BC Court Services Online Search indicating that NGC is a defendant in multiple proceedings commenced in the last two years in our Provincial (Small Claims) Court and Supreme Court.</P1>
<P1>f) Exhibit &ldquo;G&rdquo; is a copy of the Order Approving Proposal, in the Matter of the Proposal of NGC, BCSC, Vancouver Registry, No. B110435, together with a copy of the Report of Trustee on Proposal.</P1></P>
<P>13. I am not aware of any assets or property of Mr. Hermano that would secure an order for costs. Searches of public registries have been conducted and based on the results of those searches I verily believe that Mr. Hermano does not have assets or property to secure an order for costs. Attached and marked as:
<P1>a) Exhibit &ldquo;H&rdquo; is a true copy of a BC Personal Property Registry Search indicating that Mr. Hermano is not the registered owner of any personal property in British Columbia;</P1>
<P1>b) Exhibit &ldquo;I&rdquo; is a true copy of a BC Land Title Search Print showing charges against, including as to the interest of Mr. Hermano in, real property that Mr. Hermano is the registered owner in fee simple, as a joint tenant.</P1>
<P1>c) Exhibit &ldquo;J&rdquo; is a true copy of a BC Court Services Online Search indicating that Mr. Hermano is the defendant in proceedings commenced in our Provincial (Small Claims) Court and Supreme Court.</P1>
<P1>d) Exhibit &ldquo;K&rdquo; is a copy of a Notice of Claim filed in the BC Provincial Court (Small Claims Court), Prince George Registry, Registry File Number 1138531, on January 27, 2011, alleging that NGC and Mr. Hermano committed a breach of trust by appropriating or converting all or part of funds received as trustees for uses not authorized by the trust; the total claimed is $12,522.56.</P1>
<P1>e) Exhibit &ldquo;L&rdquo; is a copy of a Notice of Civil Claim filed in the BC Supreme Court, Prince George Registry, No. 1140172, on November 25, 2011, alleging that Mr. Hermano committed a breach of trust by diverting funds for payment of subcontractors to other parties; judgment in the amount of $47,206.25, plus special costs, is sought against Mr. Hermano.</P1>
<P1>f) Exhibit &ldquo;M&rdquo; is a copy of a Notice of Civil Claim filed in the BC Supreme Court, Vancouver Registry, Court File No. VLC-S-S-118681, on December 19, 2011, alleging that New Generation Construction Ltd. committed, and Mr. Hermano acquiesced in, a breach of trust by misapplying funds received in trust; judgment in the amount of $68,233.96, plus interest, up to December 2011 in the amount of $72,525.00, and costs, is sought jointly and severally against Mr. Hermano and New Generation Construction Ltd.</P1>
<P1>g) Exhibit &ldquo;N&rdquo; is a true copy of a BC Company Summary showing that:
<P2>i) New Generation Construction Ltd. is a British Columbia company;</P2>
<P2>ii) Alfredo Hermano is also this company's sole director and officer; and</P2>
<P2>iii) the registered and records office of this company, and the mailing address for Mr. Hermano, is the same as that for NGC.</P2></P1></P>
<P>14. Attached and marked as Exhibit &ldquo;O&rdquo; is a copy of a draft Bill of Costs of the Defendant, which conservatively estimates the costs and disbursements to defend these proceedings through a 10 day trial. The Defendant however intends to seek special costs at trial, including because it is alleged by the Defendant that an amount is due to NGC pursuant to its agreement with NGC, but NGC has nonetheless continued its claims, in circumstances where its claim is supported by a false claim of lien filed further to a false declaration of Mr. Hermano personally on behalf of NGC.</P>
<P>15. I make this Affidavit in support of the orders sought in the Defendant's Notice of Application dated March 5, 2012, and for no improper purpose.</P>
