<BLOCK1><TI>APPLICATION RESPONSE</TI>
<P>Application response of: Alfredo Hermano and NGC Management Ltd., (the &ldquo;application respondents&rdquo;)</P>
<P>THIS IS A RESPONSE TO the notice of application of Lengara Ventures Ltd. filed April 24, 2012.</P>
<BLOCK2 LABEL="Part"><N>1:</N><TI>ORDERS CONSENTED TO</TI>
<P>The application respondents consent to the granting of the orders set out in the following paragraphs of Part 1 of the notice of application on the following terms:</P>
<P>NONE</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2 LABEL="Part"><N>2:</N><TI>ORDERS OPPOSED</TI>
<P>The application respondents oppose the granting of the orders set out in paragraphs 1 and 2 of Part 1 of the notice of application.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2 LABEL="Part"><N>3:</N><TI>ORDERS ON WHICH NO POSITION IS TAKEN</TI>
<P>The application respondents take no position on the granting of the orders set out in none of the paragraphs of Part 1 of the notice of application.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2 LABEL="Part"><N>4:</N><TI>FACTUAL BASIS</TI>
<P><P1>1. This is a claim made by the plaintiff against the defendant for debt for services supplied, and a claim by the plaintiff to enforce a builder's lien.</P1>
<P1>2. This action was commenced on April 19, 2010.</P1>
<P1>3. The plaintiff alleges that it had a construction management contract with the defendant. That contract is in writing and is Exhibit &ldquo;A&rdquo; to Mr. Hermano's affidavit. Mr. Hermano, the president of the plaintiff deposes, and the contract says, that unless otherwise agreed, the defendant would engage the sub-trades and pay the sub-trades. Mr. Hermano says that the plaintiff only engaged a rental company and a lumber company.</P1>
<P1>4. The statement of defence admits that a contract in writing dated March 12, 2009 was entered into, but then the defence says &ldquo;between March 12, 2009 and December 26, 2009&rdquo; the written contract was amended. &ldquo;Among&rdquo; the alleged changes were a reduction in the plaintiff's fees (without a pleading that there was any consideration for this reduction), and that a statutory declaration was to be provided by the plaintiff to the defendant on substantial completion, such declaration affirming that there were no claims relating to the works from those contracted with by the plaintiff that could affect the defendant, again without any pleading that there was some consideration for this amendment to a pre-existing contractual duty.</P1>
<P1>5. The defence does not say when the date of substantial completion was but the defence does allege that on March 1, 2010 an occupancy permit was granted for the building.</P1>
<P1>6. The defence alleges that on February 24, 2010 Mr. Hermano swore a false statutory declaration. It is alleged that there were two liens filed after that declaration was sworn thus indicating, the defendant alleges, that it was false.</P1>
<P1>7. The defendant did not pay to the plaintiff any amounts as a result of that alleged false statutory declaration. Mr. Hermano says that the declaration was not false. He says that the arrangements he had with the two lien claimants were that their accounts were due and payable when the plaintiff was paid.</P1>
<P1>8. There is no allegation in the statement of defence, in the counterclaim or in the third party notice that the defendant ever relied in any way on the alleged false statutory declaration to its detriment or otherwise.</P1>
<P1>9. To the contrary, the defendant alleges that when it found out the statutory declaration was allegedly untrue, it stopped paying the plaintiff. There was no reliance and the necessary inference from the defendant's pleadings is that the defendant did not in any way rely upon the alleged false statutory declaration to its detriment or otherwise.</P1>
<P1>10. The defence alleges that the claim of client that the plaintiff filed is false.</P1>
<P1>11. The defence alleges at paragraph 25 that something is owed to the plaintiff, but it is less than the amount the plaintiff is claiming. No claim is made in the defence for breach of contract, or damages, or set off of damages.</P1>
<P1>12. The counterclaim repeats the statement of defence.</P1>
<P1>13. The counterclaim then pleads section 45 of the <EM>Builders Lien Act</EM>.</P1>
<P1>14. Section 45 of the <EM>Builders Lien Act</EM> creates an offence of filing a claim of lien containing a false statement. Section 45 does not create a civil cause of action to be exercised by private parties.</P1>
<P1>15. Mr. Hermano is not joined as a defendant by the counterclaim.</P1>
<P1>16. The counterclaim alleges that Mr. Hermano and the plaintiff knew the claim of lien was false when it was filed.</P1>
<P1>17. The counterclaim then alleges that Mr. Hermano and the plaintiff were &ldquo;responsible for the issuance of the false Declaration&rdquo;. The counterclaim then specifically pleads at paragraph 5 that the defendant did not make payment on the contract after the false declaration&mdash;by necessary inference the defendant was not induced to do anything to its detriment as a result of the alleged false declaration nor does the defendant in any way allege that it relied on the false declaration and that reliance caused or contributed to any loss.</P1>
<P1>18. Paragraph 6 of the counterclaim alleges that Mr. Hermano and the plaintiff refused to complete their obligations under the contract (no allegation is made anywhere that Mr. Hermano entered into any contract with the defendant or was somehow privy to a contract with the defendant) and then in the same paragraph it is alleged that Mr. Hermano and the plaintiff have maintained the claim of lien and this action &ldquo;with reckless indifference to the legitimate interests of the Defendant&rdquo;.</P1>
<P1>19. The plaintiff then claims these matters somehow caused it loss by the plaintiff having to pay 15 liens and that the contract completion was delayed. No facts are pled that these liens were obligations of the plaintiff. No facts are pled that the contract was delayed.</P1>
<P1>20. No relief is sought specifically against Mr. Hermano in Part 2, but punitive damages are sought, presumably, against all parties; without pleadings of facts that would substantiate a claim to punitive damages. (<CASEREF><SOC>Whiten v. Pilot Insurance Co.</SOC><CITE>[2002] S.C.J. No. 19</CITE></CASEREF>)</P1>
<P1>21. The entire purported legal basis of the counterclaim is summarized by the defendant in two short paragraphs. The defendant says that the acts of Mr. Hermano were not as an agent of the company but he acted in a &ldquo;tortuous&rdquo; manner and exhibited a &ldquo;separate identity&rdquo; from the company. What the tort that Mr. Hermano may have committed is not revealed in the counterclaim. Mr. Hermano is not joined as a defendant by counterclaim.</P1>
<P1>22. The second legal basis is that the corporate veil is sought to be pierced on the theory that this is a case of &ldquo;improper conduct&rdquo;. Again, Mr. Hermano is not joined as a defendant by counterclaim.</P1>
<P1>23. The defendant then seeks leave to file and serve a third party notice against Mr. Hermano personally. <BOLD><UNDER>The only relief sought against Mr. Hermano personally in that third party notice is costs.</UNDER></BOLD> No damages, debt or any other relief other than costs is sought against Mr. Hermano.</P1>
<P1>24. The third party notice repeats the defence, relies on the offence section of the <EM>Builders Lien Act</EM>, s. 45, and then a claim is made that Mr. Hermano and the plaintiff knowingly filed a false claim of lien.</P1>
<P1>25. The same allegations as pleaded in the counterclaim are repeated in the third party notice and the same legal basis is propounded to support the third party claim. Again, the third party proceedings do not seek relief by indemnification or co-responsibility with the defendant&mdash;only costs is sought.</P1>
<P1>26. In support of the application for security for costs the defendant adduces evidence that the plaintiff has outstanding lawsuits against it. The plaintiff adduces evidence that as a result of the defendant not paying its debt to the defendant the defendant suffered financially, eventually taking the lawful and responsible recourse to an accepted proposal to creditors made pursuant to the Bankruptcy and <EM>Insolvency Act</EM>.</P1>
<P1>27. The plaintiff is an operating company employing 10 people. Mr. Hermano deposes that the plaintiff cannot pay $50,000 in security for costs&mdash;the result of an order for security for costs then being that a debtor, the defendant, who has caused financial hardship to the plaintiff, is able to stifle the claim of its victim to collect a just debt.</P1></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2 LABEL="Part"><N>5:</N><TI>LEGAL BASIS</TI>
<P><P1>1. In order for pleadings to be amended a cause of action must be stated. (<CASEREF><SOC>Shaw Cablesystems Ltd. v. Concord Pacific Group Inc.</SOC><YEAR>2009</YEAR><CITE>2009 BCSC 203</CITE></CASEREF>) The legal basis of the application does not identify any cause of action nor can any cause of action known, as of yet, to the common law, equity or by statute be reasonably discerned from either the proposed counter-claim or third party claim.</P1>
<P1>2. Assuming that the cause of actions that are intended to be pleaded have something to do with the alleged false statutory declaration and are an attempt to pierce the corporate veil, then the pleadings are wanting.</P1>
<P1>3. A pleading of fraudulent misrepresentation requires that the representation was (a) false, (b) made knowing it was false, (c) made with the intention that the counter-party would act upon it or rely upon it; (d) the counter-party did act upon it or relied upon it; and (e) as a result of that reliance or action the counter-party suffered loss. (Lord Brennan Q.C. ed., <EM>Bullen &amp; Leake &amp; Jacob's Precedents of Pleadings</EM>, 15<SUP>th</SUP> ed. (London: Sweet &amp; Maxwell, (2004) Vol. 2 page 799; G.H.L. Fridman, <EM>The Law of Torts in Canada</EM>, 3<SUP>rd</SUP> ed. (Toronto: Carswell (2010)) at pp. 709&ndash;718). Alternatively, the pleading must at least allege (a) a knowingly false representation, (b) loss and (c) that the false representation caused the loss, with the burden of reliance then shifting to the person alleged to have made the representation. (<CASEREF><SOC>Roy v. 1216393 Ontario Inc.</SOC><CITE>[2011] B.C.J. No. 2351</CITE></CASEREF>).</P1>
<P1>4. Assuming any of the elements of a cause of action for fraudulent misrepresentation have been pled in fact and law, which they have not, the defendant specifically pleads that it did not rely on the alleged fraudulent misrepresentation, but as a result of the fraudulent misrepresentation it did not pay its debt due to the plaintiff. Based on the facts and law as pleaded in the proposed counterclaim and third party notice no detrimental reliance can be discerned or proved.</P1>
<P1>5. To attribute personal responsibility to a director of a corporation for acts done in that capacity requires that the corporate identity be disregarded. This is only rarely done, and requires evidence of a deliberate wrongdoing and that the company is being used as a cloak to perpetrate a fraud. (Kevin McGuinness, <EM>Halsbury's Laws of Canada, Business Corporations I</EM>, 1<SUP>st</SUP> ed., (Toronto; Lexis Nexis (2008) pp. 241&ndash;244). No facts have been pled to ground an allegation that there was deliberate wrongdoing by Mr. Hermano and that the plaintiff was a cloak for fraud.</P1>
<P1>6. Assuming the theory for personal liability is that Mr. Hermano induced a breach of contract by the plaintiff, this theory is not tenable at law, without an allegation of fraud acting in his personal capacity. (<CASEREF><SOC>Said v. Butt</SOC><CITE>[1920] 3 K.B. 497</CITE><COURTJUR>K.B.</COURTJUR></CASEREF>, <CASEREF><SOC>Einhorn v. Westmount Investments Ltd.</SOC><YEAR>1970</YEAR><CITE>11 D.L.R. (3rd) 509</CITE></CASEREF>.).</P1>
<P1>7. The only relief sought in the proposed third party proceedings is an order for costs or special costs against Mr. Hermano. It is submitted that as the defendant has sought to restrict the relief sought to costs, there is no need for the court to exercise its discretion to grant leave for third party proceedings (<CASEREF><SOC>Lui v. West Granville Manor Ltd.</SOC><YEAR>1985</YEAR><CITE>61 B.C.L.R. 315</CITE></CASEREF>) as there is jurisdiction for this Court to order costs against a non-party without the necessity, and unnecessary prolixity, of further pleadings and proceedings. (<CASEREF><SOC>H.M. v. J.A.S.</SOC><YEAR>2008</YEAR><CITE>289 D.L.R. (4th) 315</CITE></CASEREF>.)</P1>
<P1>8. The applicants have not made out a <EM>prima facie</EM> case that the defendant is unable to pay costs. The defendant is an operating company that has acted responsibly to deal with the financial calamity produced by the defendant, has endured despite the defendant's failure to pay its just debt and there is no reason to believe that the plaintiff could not pay costs&mdash;at least over time. Even if the defendant has proven impecuniosity, then it is submitted that the court should exercise its discretionary jurisdiction not to order security for costs on the principle that such an order would allow a wrongdoer to stifle the claim brought by the victim of the wrongdoer to remedy the harm done by the wrongdoer. (<CASEREF><SOC>Kropp v. Swaneset Bay Golf Course Ltd.</SOC><CITE>[1997] B.C.J. No. 593</CITE></CASEREF>, <CASEREF><SOC>Integrated Contractors Ltd. v. Leduc Developments Ltd.</SOC><CITE>[2009] B.C.J. No. 1422</CITE></CASEREF>]</P1></P></BLOCK2>
