<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="I">AFFIDAVIT</TI>
<P>I, ALFREDO HERMANO, businessman of 201-856 Homer Street in the City of Vancouver in the Province of British Columbia make oath and say as follows;
<P1>1. I am the president of the plaintiff and as such I have personal knowledge of the facts and matters referred to in this affidavit except where the same are stated to be made upon information and belief and where so stated I verily believe the same to be true.</P1>
<P1>2. The contract between NGC Management Ltd. and Lengara Ventures Ltd. was a construction management contract. A copy of the first 22 pages of that contract are attached as Exhibit &ldquo;A&rdquo; to this my affidavit.</P1>
<P1>3. This contract was a very large contract for the plaintiff. At the time the plaintiff entered into this contract, I had many discussions with Mr. Walker to make sure that he intended to pay the plaintiff and to pay the sub-trades. The contract required him to pay all of the sub-trades. The plaintiff was to pay a rental company and a lumber supplier.</P1>
<P1>4. Mr. Walker is the president of the defendant. Throughout this contract the sub-trades complained to me that they were not being paid by the defendant. When I would confront Mr. Walker with this, Mr. Walker would make excuses for not paying the sub-trades. Usually these complaints would be technical things, such as scope of work and his interpretation of the sub-contract differing with that of the sub- contractor. Mr. Walker would also complain that the subcontractor's costs were too high-even though he had signed their sub-contracts that told him what the costs were. Throughout the contract Mr. Walker was causing the defendant not to pay the sub-trades and this caused delay, and this hurt the plaintiff's reputation and relationship with these sub-trades. I had told the sub-trades that my initial view was that Mr. Walker was honourable and paid his bills. I was wrong.</P1>
<P1>5. Mr. Walker insisted I swear statutory declarations before each draw. I told Mr. Walker that the funds that the defendant would pay would be used to pay the rental company and the lumber company. Both the rental company, Harrigan Rentals and Rona Revy&mdash;formerly Dick's lumber&mdash;had agreed with me to be paid when I was paid. Therefore, I am of the view that the statutory declarations in this matter that I swore were all true.</P1>
<P1>6. The Defendant did not pay the Plaintiff and did not pay its sub-trades. As a result the plaintiff filed a lien and sub-trades filed a lien. When the plaintiff was not paid by the defendant, Rona Revy and Harrigan Rentals filed liens as the plaintiff was not paid.</P1>
<P1>7. The lien claim is not inflated because Mr. Walker unilaterally took it upon himself to take the plaintiff's invoices, reduce the rates, and tender the reduced amount. The defendant simply did not pay its bills. Eventually the situation became intolerable for the plaintiff's business resulting in the plaintiff liening the project in March, 2010 and stopping work due to non-payment by the defendant.</P1>
<P1>8. When the defendant did not pay the plaintiff this caused severe financial hardship to the plaintiff, resulting in the plaintiff having to make a proposal to its creditors pursuant Division 1 of the <EM>Bankruptcy and Insolvency Act</EM>. That proposal was accepted by the creditors. The plaintiff paid $300,000 to its creditors to resolve about $1,400,000 in debt. The proposal will be paid over a five year period and all payments have been made to date. The proposal will be finished in September, 2016.</P1>
<P1>9. The plaintiff has carried on with business, although the defendant nearly bankrupted the plaintiff by the defendant not paying its debt to the plaintiff.</P1>
<P1>10. The plaintiff has some cash flow and some on-going work. The construction industry in Vancouver and the surrounding area is very difficult at this time.</P1>
<P1>11. The plaintiff cannot afford to pay $50,000 in security for costs. The reason the plaintiff could not pay its bills since 2010, was because the defendant did not pay its bills to the plaintiff.</P1>
<P1>12. The plaintiff is carrying on business as best it can. The plaintiff employs about ten full time people. This debt has been outstanding for two years and is a substantial burden to the plaintiff.</P1></P>
