<BLOCK1><TI>AFFIDAVIT</TI>
<P>I, Gary Walker, businessman, c/o #201, 20353 - 64<SUP>th</SUP> Avenue, in the Township of Langley, in the Province of British Columbia, make oath and say that:</P>
<P>1. I am the president of the Defendant, Lengara Ventures Inc. (hereinafter referred to as &ldquo;Lengara&rdquo;), and as such have personal knowledge of the facts and matters hereinafter deposed to save and except where stated to upon information and belief and where so stated I verily believe them to be true.</P>
<P>2. I have been authorized to swear this Affidavit on behalf of the Defendant.</P>
<P>3. This Affidavit is in response to Affidavit No. 1 of Alfredo Hermano sworn June 28, 2012 (hereinafter referred to as the &ldquo;Hermano Affidavit&rdquo;).</P>
<P>4. For simplicity, I adopt the definitions in my Affidavit sworn March 5, 2012 (hereinafter referred to as the &ldquo;G. Walker #3 Affidavit&rdquo;).</P>
<P>5. In response to paragraph 2 of the Hermano Affidavit and the excerpt of the Canadian Construction Association Introduction to CCA No. 5-1988 Standard Construction Management Contract Form (hereinafter referred to as the &ldquo;Original Contract&rdquo;), marked as Exhibit &ldquo;A&rdquo; and attached to the Hermano Affidavit, the Original Contract was not followed by the Plaintiff, and was amended, from time to time, orally and in writing, lastly as set out in the document marked Exhibit &ldquo;A&rdquo; that is attached to the G. Walker #3 Affidavit.</P>
<P>6. In response to paragraph 3 of the Hermano Affidavit:
<P1>a. I had never been involved in, overseen or managed the construction of any commercial building, and relied solely on Mr. Hermano and his company, which was retained because he told me of his knowledge and expertise in the management of the type of construction required for the Improvement;</P1>
<P1>b. there were no discussions with Mr. Hermano about the Defendant paying the Plaintiff or sub-trades at the time the Original Contract was entered into; and</P1>
<P1>c. if Mr. Hermano is referring to the Original Contract, it was not followed by the Plaintiff and was amended, from time to time: for example, the Plaintiff engaged trade contractors on its own and the target complete date of October 2009 was not achieved.</P1></P>
<P>7. In response to paragraph 4 of the Hermano Affidavit:
<P1>a. it is untrue that I, or the Defendant, did not pay, or complained about having to pay, any sub-trades;</P1>
<P1>b. trade contractors communicated through Mr. Hermano or the Plaintiff;</P1>
<P1>c. I was never made aware of any complaints by sub-trades about not being paid by the Defendant;</P1>
<P1>d. I caused the Defendant to pay sub-trades as advised by Mr. Hermano or the Plaintiff, after I was in receipt of proper documentation, and all payments were made in a timely manner;</P1>
<P1>e. it is untrue that I caused the Defendant not to pay sub-trades; and</P1>
<P1>f. it is also untrue that I or the Defendant was/were the cause of any delay or damage to the Plaintiff's reputation or relationship with any sub-trades.</P1></P>
<P>8. In response to paragraph 5 of the Hermano Affidavit:
<P1>a. the reason why the statutory declarations were required by the Defendant was that the Defendant was aware that the Plaintiff was sub-contracting (notwithstanding the Original Contract) to various trades;</P1>
<P1>b. when the Contract was made in December 2009, I discussed with Mr. Hermano that statutory declaration were required to ensure that all amounts owing to trades contracting through the Plaintiff were paid;</P1>
<P1>c. Mr. Hermano and the Plaintiff never advised me or the Defendant that any sub-trades remained unpaid prior to delivery of any statutory declarations;</P1>
<P1>d. when Mr. Hermano presented the Declaration in conjunction with the request for payment of the Invoices, he did not tell me that the funds that the Defendant would pay would be used to pay the rental company or the lumber company;</P1>
<P1>e. both personally and through counsel there were numerous dealings with Mr. Hermano and the Plaintiff after the issuance of the Declaration; and</P1>
<P1>f. at no time prior to the Hermano Affidavit has Mr. Hermano ever said to me, my counsel or the Defendant, that it was his intention to pay the rental company or the lumber company from the proceeds of the Invoices.</P1></P>
<P>9. In response to paragraph 6 of the Hermano Affidavit, I do not know what sub-trades Mr. Hermano is referring to that the Defendant did not pay. I caused the Defendant to pay paid sub-trades as required and/or as advised by Mr. Hermano or the Plaintiff, in a timely manner.</P>
<P>10. In response to paragraph 7 of the Hermano Affidavit, I do not know which of the Plaintiff's invoices Mr. Hermano is referring to.</P>
<P>11. In further response to paragraph 7 and in response to paragraph 9 of the Hermano Affidavit:
<P1>a. the Original Contract, amended from time to time, was entered into in March 2009, with a target completion date of October 2009;</P1>
<P1>b. October 2009 came and went and Mr. Hermano and I agreed on December 26, 2009, that the Plaintiff would have the building completed and ready for occupancy by January 25, 2010;</P1>
<P1>c. a temporary Occupancy permit was not issued until March 1, 2010;</P1>
<P1>d. by letter dated March 15, 2010 the Plaintiff advised that it would not provide further services and that it would withhold all documents and information from the Defendant, which it did, unless the NGC Lien was paid;</P1>
<P1>e. the Plaintiff invoiced the Defendant and there were issues raised, from time to time, about various construction issues, which included services rendered by the Plaintiff, delays in construction, and invoices;</P1>
<P1>f. the above-noted issues were resolved from time to time in the normal course, which included agreed changes to the Original Contract;</P1>
<P1>g. I advised Mr. Hermano after becoming aware of the Unpaid Sub-Contracts that the Defendant was prepared to pay the amounts properly due to NGC pursuant to the Contract subject to satisfactory arrangements for payment of the Unpaid Sub-Contracts, but Mr. Hermano refusing to agree to satisfactory arrangements for payment of the Unpaid Sub-Contracts.</P1></P>
