<BLOCK1><TI>NOTICE OF APPLICATION</TI>
<P>Name of Applicant: The Defendant, Lengara Ventures inc.</P>
<P>To: The Plaintiff, NGC Management Ltd.</P>
<P>TAKE NOTICE that an application will be made by the applicant to the presiding judge or master at the courthouse at the Law Courts, 800 Smithe Street, Vancouver British Columbia on <BOLD>December 14, 2016</BOLD>, at 9:45 a.m. for the orders set out in Part 1 below.</P>
<BLOCK2 LABEL="Part"><N>1:</N><TI>ORDERS SOUGHT</TI>
<P>1. An order dismissing the plaintiffs claims for want of prosecution, and that the dismissal be and is of the same effect as if its claims had been dismissed after a trial on its merits.</P>
<P>2. A declaration and order that the Irrevocable Standby Letter of Credit, issued by the Canadian Western Bank, with the Registrar of the Court, as security for the claim of lien registered under number XXXXXXXXXX, in the amount of $323,585.35, be returned to the Canadian Western Bank, without further order, direction or other action.</P>
<P>3. Costs payable to the defendant forthwith.</P>
<P>4. Such further and other relief as this Honourable Court may deem just.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2 LABEL="Part"><N>2:</N><TI>FACTUAL BASIS</TI>
<P>1. The Defendant / Applicant, Lengara Ventures Inc. (&ldquo;Lengara&rdquo;) owns lands and premises located at 3410 Lougheed Hwy, Vancouver, BC, presently legally described as Lot 1 Block 1 Section 38 Town of Hastings Suburban Lands Plan BCP43119 (the &ldquo;Lands&rdquo;).</P>
<P>2. Lengara is actively engaged in the business of property development, in conjunction with related companies, the &ldquo;No. 1 Collision Group of Companies&rdquo; which operate auto body repair service shops.</P>
<P>3. On or about March 12, 2009, NGC and Lengara entered into a written contract in connection with the construction of a commercial building and related improvements to the Land (the &ldquo;improvement&rdquo;), from which, since 2010, one of the No. 1 Collision Group of Companies has operated an auto body repair service shop.</P>
<P>4. Virtually all dealings between NGC and Lengara in respect of the construction of the Improvement were between Gary Walker (&ldquo;Gary&rdquo;) and Alfredo Hermano, president of NGC. Gary will be 70 years of age in December 2016, and his mental acuity, including his memory, focus, concentration and understanding, is not as it was.</P>
<P>5. The written contract was amended from time to time, orally and in writing, including on December 26, 2009, when it was agreed NGC would provide a statutory declaration in respect of invoices issued by NGC to Lengara upon substantial completion of the Improvement (which was to be completed by January 25, 201 0).</P>
<P>6. On or about January 15, 2010, Lengara paid invoices issued by NGC, for services rendered to date in connection with the Improvement (the &ldquo;Progress Payment&rdquo;).</P>
<P>7. After the Progress Payment, Mr. Hermano provided Lengara with a Statutory Declaration, dated the 24<SUP>th</SUP> of February, 2010, in conjunction with a request for payment of invoices totaling $104,648.91 (the &ldquo;Invoices&rdquo;).</P>
<P>8. The Declaration made by Mr. Hermano was false; on the date the Declaration was made and on the date it was provided to Lengara there were at least two subcontractors to NGC who had issued invoices for services to the Improvement prior to the Progress Payment, which invoices were not then paid (the &ldquo;Unpaid Sub&mdash;Contracts&rdquo;), and for which Lengara could be held responsible.</P>
<P>9. As a result of the false declaration, Lengara refused to pay the Invoices, without satisfactory arrangements being made for payment of the Unpaid Sub -Contracts.</P>
<P>10. On March 12, 2010, NGC filed a Claim of Lien against the title to the Lands under number XXXXXXXXXX in the amount of $399,417.36 (the &ldquo;NGC Lien&rdquo;). No invoice for this amount claimed was received by Lengara prior to the filing of the NGC Lien.</P>
<P>11. The Unpaid Sub-Contracts were the subject of claims of lien filed on April 8 and 9, 2010, against the Lands, in the amounts of $21,727.03, and $57,648.11.</P>
<P>12. On April 19, 2010, NGC filed a Writ of Summons and Statement of Claim and registered a Certificate of Pending Litigation against the Lands, under number XXXXXXXXXX, alleging breach of the written contract between NGC and Lengara, and claiming the sum of $399,417.36, plus interest at the rate of 10% above the prime rate per annum, for services allegedly provided in relation to the Improvement.</P>
<P>13. On April 23, 2010, Lengara filed and served an Appearance and delivered a Demand for Discovery of Documents and Notice to Produce.</P>
<P>14. On April 26, 2010, NGC delivered a Demand for Discovery of Documents and Notice to Produce.</P>
<P>15. On May 17, 2010, Lengara filed a Statement of Defence, saying, among other things, that the written contract was amended from time to time by further agreements made between April 9, 2009 and December 26, 2009, and that Mr. Hermano, the principal and operating mind behind the operations of NGC, knowingly executed a false statutory declaration that included a statement that all subcontractors to NGC had been paid.</P>
<P>16. On June 30, 2010, NGC filed a Notice of Trial, setting the trial for 10 days, commencing June 6, 2011.</P>
<P>17. On July 26, 2010, Lengara filed a Notice of Application returnable August 12, 2010, seeking orders authorizing payments for the Unpaid Sub-Contracts, in the amounts of their lien claims, on account of contracts with NGC, and to discharge the NGC's Lien upon posting security.</P>
<P>18. On July 27, 2010, NGC delivered a List of Documents.</P>
<P>19. On August 13, 2010, the Honourable Master Donaldson made an order, by consent of the parties, canceling the NGC Lien and Certificate of Pending Litigation, on payment into court by Lengara of $323,585.35, as security for the NGC Lien.</P>
<P>20. On August 30, 2010, Lengara deposited funds in the amount of $323,585.35 into court, in accordance with the Order of the Honourable Master Donaldson.</P>
<P>21. On September 2, 2010, NGC delivered an Appointment to Examine For Discovery, to examine Gary, as the representative for Lengara, on October 5, 2010, which discovery was cancelled on September 22, 2010.</P>
<P>22. On October 15, 2010, Lengara requested documents from NGC's List of Documents.</P>
<P>23. On October 28, 2010, NGC filed a Requisition to set a settlement conference for February 14, 2011. The same was delivered by fax sent November 19, 2010.</P>
<P>24. On November 23, 2010, Lengara delivered a List of Documents. We have no record of NGC making a request for a copy of the documents disclosed by Lengara.</P>
<P>25. By letter dated November 23, 2010, NGC provided copies of its listed documents to Lengara, as Lengara had requested.</P>
<P>26. On December 20, 2010, NGC filed a Requisition to set a trial management conference for April 27, 2011.</P>
<P>27. On December 31, 2010, Lengara filed an Application, returnable January 13, 2011, seeking to vary the Order of the Honourable Master Donaldson to substitute the security deposited with a letter of credit.</P>
<P>28. On January 13, 2011, the Honourable Master Tokarek varied the Order of the Honourable Master Donaldson to permit Lengara to deposit a letter of credit in substitution for the funds deposited. Despite request, NGC did not consent, and did not file responsive materials or attend at the hearing of this application.</P>
<P>29. On January 24, 2011, NGC filed a Requisition to reschedule the settlement conference, from February 14, 2011, to April 8, 2011.</P>
<P>30. Pursuant to the Order of the Honourable Master Tokarek, Lengara deposited an Irrevocable Standby Letter of Credit issued by the Canadian Western Bank, dated January 31, 2011, with the Registrar of the Court, as security for the NGC Lien, in substitution for funds Lengara had previously deposited with the Registrar of the Court, in the amount of $323,585.35 (the &ldquo;Letter of Credit&rdquo;).</P>
<P>31. As a term of providing the Letter of Credit, Lengara is required to keep $323,585.35 in a GIC account with the Canadian Western Bank, as security for the Letter of Credit. Lengara receives nominal interest on funds in this GIC account, currently 0. 7% per annum, however its cost of borrowing is substantially higher. The cost to maintain the Letter of Credit is 1.00% per annum ($3,235.85 annually).</P>
<P>32. On April 5, 2011, Daniel Le Dressay, counsel for NGC, emailed Bruce Rosberg, counsel for Lengara, advising that NGC had filed a Notice of Intention to make a proposal pursuant to Division 1 of the <EM>Bankruptcy and Insolvency Act</EM>.</P>
<P>33. On April 6, 2011, NGC filed a Requisition to adjourn generally, by consent, the settlement conference set for April 8, 2011, the trial management conference set for April 27, 2011, and the trial set for June 6, 2011.</P>
<P>34. On December 7, 2011, NGC delivered an Appointment to Examine For Discovery, to examine Gary, as the representative for Lengara, for February 13, 2013.</P>
<P>35. On March 23, 2012, NGC filed a Notice of Trial, resetting the trial, for 5 days, commencing June 3, 2013, with counsel for Lengara as to the date or reduced days, from 10 to 5 days.</P>
<P>36. On April 11, 2012, NGC filed a Notice of Case Planning Conference setting a case planning conference for August 29, 2012.</P>
<P>37. On April 24, 2012, Lengara filed a Notice of Application, seeking leave to file a Counterclaim and Third Party Notice, and for security for costs.</P>
<P>38. On July 6, 2012, the Honourable Mr. Justice Kelleher, among other things, granted Lengara leave to file a Counterclaim, and ordered NGC to post security for costs in the amount of $20,000 and stayed this proceeding until said security was posted.</P>
<P>39. On or about July 19, 2012, the examination for discovery of Mr. Walker set for February 13, 2013, was cancelled.</P>
<P>40. On July 26, 2012, Lengara filed a Counterclaim, in accordance with the Order of the Honourable Mr. Justice Kelleher made July 6, 2012, and served the same by fax to Mr. Le Dressay, whose office faxed back the service copy of the letter covering the Counterclaim, with only the date of service written in as July 27, 2012.</P>
<P>41. On August 15, 2012, NGC served a Requisition filed August 14, 2012, adjourning, the case management conference set for August 29, 2012, generally by consent.</P>
<P>42. On November 9, 2012, NGC served a Requisition filed November 8, 2012, adjourning the trial set for June 3, 2013, generally by consent.</P>
<P>43. On February 22, 2016, NGC filed and served a Notice of Appointment or Change of Lawyer appointing Garrett Munroe to act as its lawyer in place of Mr. Le Dressay.</P>
<P>44. NGC has not, within a reasonable period of time, or at ail, complied with the Order of the Honourable Mr. Justice Kelleher made July 6, 2012, to post security for costs.</P>
<P>45. NGC has not filed a Response to Counterclaim, within the time permitted by the Supreme Court civil rules, or at all.</P>
<P>46. NGC has done absolutely nothing to advance its claims towards trial, at best, since March 23, 2012, when it unilaterally filed a Notice of Trial, which date was subsequently adjourned generally.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2 LABEL="Part"><N>3:</N><TI>LEGAL BASIS</TI>
<BLOCK3><TI><EM>Dismissal for Want of Prosecution</EM></TI>
<P>1. Rule 22-7(7) grants discretion to the court, on application by a party, to dismiss a proceeding if it appears that there is want of prosecution.</P>
<P>2. In considering an application to dismiss, the court must primarily consider whether:
<P1>a. the delay is inordinate, given the facts, and nature, of the case;</P1>
<P1>b. the delay is inexcusable; and</P1>
<P1>c. the defendant is likely to be prejudiced by the delay;</P1>
and then consider whether, and on balance, justice requires dismissal of the action.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Irving v. Irving</SOC><CITE>1982 CanLII 475</CITE><COURTJUR>BCCA</COURTJUR></CASEREF></P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Ed Bulley Ventures Ltd. v The Pantry Hospitality Corporation</SOC><CITE>2014 BCCA 52</CITE></CASEREF></P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Trak Energy Corporation v. Happy Valley Resort Ltd.</SOC><CITE>2015 BCSC 1928</CITE></CASEREF></P1></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI><EM>Inordinate Delay</EM></TI>
<P>3. In assessing whether delay is inordinate, it is the overall delay in prosecuting the action once a plaintiff has enlisted the judicial process as a forum for adjudication, and not necessarily just the delay calculated from the last step in a proceeding, that is usually to be considered.
<P1><EM>Ed Bulley Ventures</EM>, supra</P1></P>
<P>4. The following amounts to inordinate delay:
<P1>a. it has been more than six and a half (6<TEXTFRAC>1/2</TEXTFRAC>) years since the NGC Lien was filed;</P1>
<P1>b. it has been more than six and a half (6<TEXTFRAC>1/2</TEXTFRAC>) years since NGC commenced these proceedings;</P1>
<P1>c. it has been more than six (6) years since NGC delivered its List of Documents;</P1>
<P1>d. it has been almost six (6) years since Lengara provided copies of its documents, pursuant to Lengara's request for the same;</P1>
<P1>e. it has been more than four and a half (4<TEXTFRAC>1/2</TEXTFRAC>) years since NGC unilaterally reset these proceedings for trial, which trial was adjourned generally on November 8, 2012; and</P1>
<P1>f. it has been more than four (4) years since the Honourable Mr. Justice Kelleher ordered NGC to post $20,000 as security for costs and stayed its claim until said security was posted.</P1></P>
<P>5. NGC has taken virtually no substantive steps to advance its claim. It has not:
<P1>a. requested / discovered documents from Lengara's List of Documents;</P1>
<P1>b. conducted any examination for discovery;</P1>
<P1>c. complied with the Order of the Honourable Mr. Justice Kelleher, to post security for costs;</P1>
<P1>d. filed a Response to Lengara's Counterclaim, within the time required, or at all; or</P1>
<P1>e. reset the matter for trial.</P1></P>
<P>6. A plaintiff cannot rely on applications made by a defendant to establish that it has not delayed in prosecuting its claims.
<P1><EM>Trak Energy Corporation</EM>, supra</P1></P>
<P>7. Lengara submits that the last substantive step NGC took was to provide its List of Documents, in July 2010, more than six (6) years ago; setting and subsequently adjourning or cancelling dates, has done nothing to advance NGC's claims.</P>
<P>8. The <EM>Builders Lien Act</EM> provides an extraordinary remedy and claimants are expected to pursue their claims expeditiously; there is an expectation of expediency in builder's lien cases, a fact to be considered in assessing inordinate delay.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Hanna's Construction Services Ltd. v Blue River III Inc.</SOC><CITE>2006 BCCA 142</CITE></CASEREF></P1>
<P1><EM>Trak Energy Corporation</EM>, supra</P1></P>
<P>9. A delay of more than six (6) years since the commencement of proceedings, especially in a builder's lien case, where no significant steps have been taken and none for more than four and a half (4<TEXTFRAC>1/2</TEXTFRAC>) years, represents a serious failure by a plaintiff to proceed in a timely fashion. In all of the circumstances of this case, NGC's delay has been inordinate.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI><EM>Inexcusable Delay</EM></TI>
<P>10. Whether inordinate delay is inexcusable depends on the explanation for it, if any, and the surrounding circumstances. The lack of a credible excuse will attract an inference that the delay cannot be excused.
<P1><EM>Irving</EM>, supra</P1></P>
<P>11. Lengara is not aware of any excuse or justification for NGC's failure to advance its claims at all for more than four and a half (4<TEXTFRAC>1/2</TEXTFRAC>) years.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI><EM>Prejudice</EM></TI>
<P>12. Once inordinate and inexcusable delay has been established, the defendant is presumed to have suffered serious prejudice. The onus is on the plaintiff to establish that the defendant would not be prejudiced.
<P1><EM>Ed Bulley Ventures</EM>, supra</P1>
<P1><EM>Trak Energy Corporation</EM>, supra</P1></P>
<P>13. In addition to the presumption of prejudice, Lengara has suffered actual prejudice.</P>
<P>14. Tying up property to secure a claim, whether land or cash, for a substantial period of time, is a significant example of specific prejudice.
<P1><EM>Trak Energy Corporation</EM>, supra</P1></P>
<P>15. NGC has tied up Lengara's property, first its land and then its cash, for more than six (6) years. Not only is Lengara required to keep $323,585.35 in a G!C account with the Canadian Western Bank, as security for the Letter of Credit, Lengara has to pay an annual fee of $3,235.86, to maintain the Letter of Credit. To date this amounts to $16,179.25.</P>
<P>16. More significantly, this is a case of disputed facts which must be determined from oral testimony of witnesses, in particular Gary and Mr. Hermano.</P>
<P>17. There is always the possibility that memories will be lost and recollections will fade as a result of the passage of time. In this case, because of NGC's inordinate delay, Lengara will not likely have the best evidence available to it from its essential witness Gary, who is reported to have mental acuity issues, and would, if these proceedings are not dismissed, have to recall events from, at this date, almost seven (7) years ago.</P>
<P>18. Additionally, the accrual of interest payable on an amount alleged owed may also give rise to prejudice.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>British Columbia v. Therrien</SOC><CITE>[1999] B.C.J. No. 1038</CITE><COURTJUR>S.C.</COURTJUR></CASEREF></P1></P>
<P>19. NGC has claimed the sum of $399,417.36, <UNDER>plus interest at the rate of 10% above the prime rate per annum</UNDER>, for services allegedly provided in relation to the Improvement, despite no invoice for this amount claimed having been received by Lengara prior to the filing of the NGC Lien, and after Mr. Hermano knowingly executed a false statutory declaration [emphasis mine].</P>
<P>20. NGC stands to benefit by its decision not to prosecute its claims.</P>
<P>21. Finally, the limitation period has expired, which in and of itself if a measure of the presence of prejudice.</P>
<P>22. Lengara is likely to be seriously prejudiced by NGC's delay.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI><EM>Interests of Justice</EM></TI>
<P>23. In addressing the interests of justice, &ldquo;[o]n a balance of probabilities, is there a compelling reason in this case why the interests of justice would be served by dismissing this application, despite the findings of inordinate delay, inexcusable delay and serious prejudice to the defendant?&rdquo;
<P1><EM>Trak Energy Corporation</EM>, supra</P1></P>
<P>24. NGC claims the sum of $399,417.36, for services allegedly provided in relation to the Improvement. No invoice was ever issued or demand made to Lengara for that sum, prior to the filing of the NGC Lien. When the NGC Lien was filed, the only unpaid invoices NGC had issued totaled $104,684.91. Mr. Hermano, to the knowledge of NGC, knowingly executed a false statutory declaration, and refused to pay the Unpaid Sub-Contracts, and commenced these proceedings.</P>
<P>25. NGC, by its principal Mr. Hermano issuing the false statutory declaration, had caused the very situation giving rise to its claims, and as a result Lengara has suffered loss, costs and damages.</P>
<P>26. NGC has not complied with the July 6, 2012 Order of the Honourable Mr. Justice Kelleher to post security in the amount of $20,000, which Lengara submits demanded action forthwith or alternatively within a reasonable period of time.</P>
<P>27. The object of the <EM>Supreme Court Civil Rules</EM>, Rule 1-3(1), is to secure the just, speedy and inexpensive determination of every proceeding on its merits. These proceedings have languished and sat dormant for far too long. NGC has delayed these proceedings, to the prejudice of Lengara. There is a substantial risk that a fair trial is not possible in this case given the delay.</P>
<P>28. Lengara respectfully submits that the interests of justice require that these proceedings be dismissed for want of prosecution and the Letter of Credit returned, with costs payable forthwith to Lengara, pursuant to Rule 14 -1.</P></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
