<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="I">AFFIDAVIT</TI>
<P>I, ROBERT WALKER, Businessman, care of #201, 20353 - 64<SUP>th</SUP> Avenue, Langley, B.C. V2Y 1N5, SWEAR THAT:</P>
<P>1. I am a director and the Chief Executive Officer of Defendant Lengara Ventures Inc., (&ldquo;Lengara&rdquo;) and as such have personal knowledge of the facts and matters hereinafter deposed to, save and except where such information is stated to be on information and belief, and I verily believe that information to be true.</P>
<P>2. I am authorized to swear this Affidavit on behalf of Lengara.</P>
<P>3. Lengara is actively engaged in the business of property development, in conjuncti on with related companies, the &ldquo;No. 1 Collision Group of Companies&rdquo; which operate auto body repair service shops, all of which companies are collectively referred to as the &ldquo;Walker Group of Companies&rdquo;. The Walker Group of Companies are owned and/or controlled by my immediate family members: my father, Gary Walker (&ldquo;Gary&rdquo;), my mother, Helena Walker, my brother, Scott Walker (&ldquo;Scott&rdquo;), and me.</P>
<P>4. Lengara is the owner of lands and premises located at 3410 Lougheed Hwy, Vancouver, British Columbia, legally described as PID 028-116-844, Lot 1 Block 1 Section 38 Township of Hastings Suburban Lands Plan BCP43119 (the &ldquo;Lands&rdquo;).</P>
<P>5. I have read the Writ of Summons and Statement of Claim filed in these proceedings by the Plaintiff NGC Management Ltd. (&ldquo;NGC&rdquo;), which alleges breach of a written contract between NGC and Lengara, entered into on March 12, 2009, whereby NGC &ldquo;agreed to provide project management services as described in that contract for an improvement being constructed on the Lands (the &ldquo;improvement&rdquo;).&rdquo;</P>
<P>6. The Improvement was/is a commercial building and related improvements to the Lands, from which, since 2010, one of the No. 1 Collision Group of Companies has operated an auto body repair service shop, alongside other arms length businesses.</P>
<P>7. I have read the Statement of Defence filed in these proceedings by Lengara, which, among other things, says that the terms of written contract between NGC and Lengara in respect of the services to be provided by NGC to the Improvement were amended from time to time by further agreements between NGC and Lengara, between March 12, 2009 and December 26, 2009.</P>
<P>8. I have been the Chief Executive Office (&ldquo;CEO&rdquo;) of the Walker Group of Companies, including Lengara, since about 2014, and a director of Lengara since August 2013. Prior to 2014, Gary was the CEO of the Walker Group of Companies, and Gary and my mother were the only directors of Lengara before I became a director in 2013.</P>
<P>9. I was not responsible for dealing with the construction of the Improvement, and was responsible for any of the agreements, or involved any discussions, between Lengara and NGC concerning the Improvement.</P>
<P>10. I am advised by Gary that virtually ail dealings between Lengara and NGC in respect of the construction of the Improvement and any other related matters were between him and Alfredo Hermano, the President of NGC.</P>
<P>11. Gary was the directing mind of Lengara at all times relevant to NGC's claims and is the person most knowledgeable of the subject matter of these proceedings.</P>
<P>12. Gary was born on December 14, 1946. He is 69 years of age.</P>
<P>13. Since about 2014, and continuing to date, Gary has had virtually no role in the management of the Walker Group of Companies, including Lengara. He is effectively retired and it is not anticipated that he will have a role in the management of any of the Walker Group of Companies, including Lengara.</P>
<P>14. The reason for Gary's retirement from the Walker Group of Companies, including Lengara, was advanced age and a decline in his ability to manage the business of the companies. He had increasingly been unable to effectively manage the day-today business of the companies, which management required not only time and effort on a full-time basis, but mental acuity.</P>
<P>15. My brother, Scott, and I made the decision to ask our Father to retire as the CEO of the Walker Group of Companies, in about 2014, based on our observations and interactions with him. We observed that his mental acuity: his memory; focus; concentration; and understanding; is not as it was, and that his ability to properly manage the business of the Walker Group of Companies was no long adequate.</P>
<P>16. As an example of Gary's declining mental acuity, in about May 2015, despite Gary having been present during financing discussions concerning the Walker Group of Companies, when it was time to sign paperwork prepared by the banks lawyers, with our corporate lawyers, Gary could not properly recall the terms of the financing negotiated in his presence, and initially refused to sign the documents. As a result of Gary's misunderstanding, changes had to be made to the documents, and the meeting with our corporate lawyers had to be rescheduled.</P>
<P>17. Lengara deposited an Irrevocable Standby Letter of Credit, issued by the Canadian Western Bank, dated January 31, 2011, with the Registrar of the Court, as security for the claim of lien registered under number XXXXXXXXXX which was filed by NGC, in substitution for funds Lengara had previously deposited with the Registrar of the Court, in the amount of $323,585.35 (the &ldquo;Letter of Credit&rdquo;).</P>
<P>18. As a term of providing the Letter of Credit, the Canadian Western Bank requires Lengara to keep $323,585.35 in a GIC account with the Canadian Western Bank, as security for the Letter of Credit. Lengara receives nominal interest on funds in this GIC account, currently 0.7% per annum, however its cost of borrowing pursuant to its line of credit is substantially higher.</P>
<P>19. The cost to maintain the Letter of Credit is 1.00% per annum ($3,235.85 annually).</P>
<P>20. I make this affidavit in support of Lengara's application to dismiss these proceedings for want of prosecution.</P>
