<BLOCK1><TI>AFFIDAVIT</TI>
<P>I, Alfredo Hermano, businessman, c/o Munroe &amp; Company, 2207 - 2850 Shaughnessy Street, in the City of Port Coquitlam, in the Province of British Columbia, SWEAR (OR AFFIRM) THAT:</P>
<P>1. I am the president of the plaintiff and as such I have personal knowledge of the facts and matters referred to in this affidavit except where the same are stated to be made upon information and belief and where so stated I verily believe the same to be true.</P>
<P>2. The plaintiff, NGC Management Ltd., is now known as NGC Constructors Ltd. (&ldquo;NGC&rdquo;).</P>
<BLOCK2><TI><UNDER>Cause of Delay</UNDER></TI>
<P>3. The primary reason for delay in the action against Lengara Ventures Inc. (&ldquo;Lengara&rdquo;) has been a financial setback.</P>
<P>4. NGC is a general contractor. Several of NGC's clients owe NGC a total of approximately three million dollars in connection with various construction projects.</P>
<P>5. As a result of these clients' non-payment, NGC has also had to defend itself against approximately thirty lawsuits by its subtrades, resulting in considerable expense.</P>
<P>6. In the summer of 2011, NGC was forced to undertake a Division 1 Proposal under the <EM>Bankruptcy and Insolvency Act</EM> to reduce the financial burden of the non-payment and restructure NGC's operations to survive the challenging situation. NGC has almost paid this amount in full.</P>
<P>7. In the fall of 2015, NGC's executive team decided to expand its opportunities, so we opened an office in Toronto, Ontario to hedge against the limited opportunities in British Columbia.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI><UNDER>Litigation Financing</UNDER></TI>
<P>8. NGC has always wanted to advance its claim against Lengara in order to collect the amount that Lengara owed to NGC.</P>
<P>9. I understand that the court order dated July 6, 2012 prevents NGC from taking any steps against Lengara until $20,000.00 is paid into court.</P>
<P>10. If the order had not been granted, NGC would have been able to move this lawsuit forward as its funds allowed.</P>
<P>11. I discovered the availability of commercial litigation financing in Canada on October 25, 2016. I have reached out to several commercial litigation financing companies seeking funding for this lawsuit against Lengara.</P>
<P>12. Two of these companies are Bentham IMF International Litigation Funding (&ldquo;Bentham&rdquo;) and BridgePoint Financial Services Inc.</P>
<P>13. NGC has is currently involved in Bentham's due diligence process. I have been informed that Bentham has the ability to fully fund this litigation and, once Bentham agrees to fund the lawsuit, it would guarantee the payment of any costs that NGC is ordered to pay Lengara in this lawsuit. Attached hereto and marked as <BOLD>Exhibit A</BOLD> is a copy of a letter from Tania Sulan, Chief Investment Officer of Bentham, addressed to Garrett Munroe and dated January 6, 2017.</P>
<P>14. I expect that Bentham will be able to make a decision regarding whether to fund this lawsuit by February 17, 2017.</P>
<P>15. Even if Bentham is unwilling to fund this litigation, NGC expects to be awarded several large contracts within the next month. These contracts are a result of NGC's expansion into Ontario and will result in significant profit to NGC. NGC will then be able to satisfy the security for costs order and move this lawsuit ahead to ensure a trial at the earliest possible date.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI><UNDER>Subcontractor Agreements</UNDER></TI>
<P>16. Lengara has made several false allegations against me and NGC. Lengara has stated that NGC owes money to subcontractors however these subcontractors were hired by Lengara. According to NGC's construction management contract with Lengara, Lengara is responsible for paying these subcontractors. Attached hereto and marked as <BOLD>Exhibit B</BOLD> are ten subcontracts which bear Gary Walker's signature and reflect Lengara's commitment to pay for the various subtrades.</P>
