<BLOCK1><TI>NOTICE OF APPLICATION</TI>
<P>Name of Applicant: The Defendant, Lengara Ventures Inc.</P>
<P>To: The Plaintiff, NGC Management Ltd.</P>
<P>TAKE NOTICE that an application will be made by the applicant to the presiding judge at the courthouse at the Law Courts, 800 Smithe Street, Vancouver British Columbia on October 24, 2017, at 9:45 a.m, for the orders set out in Part 1 below.</P>
<BLOCK2 LABEL="Part"><N>1:</N><TI>ORDERS SOUGHT</TI>
<P>1. An order dismissing the plaintiff's appeal from the decision of Master Muir made July 24, 2017, for failure to comply with the Standard Direction for Appeals from Decisions of Masters, Registrars or Special Referees pursuant to Civil Rule 23-6(8) and Family Rule 22-7(8), PD-54.</P>
<P>2. In the alternative, directions governing the conduct of the plaintiff's appeal from the decision of Master Muir made July 24, 2017.</P>
<P>3. An order dispensing with approval by the plaintiff as to the form of the orders of Master Muir made July 24, 2017, Master Dick made April 5, 2017, and Master Scarth made December 15, 2016.</P>
<P>4. Special costs, payable to the defendant forthwith, in any event of the cause.</P>
<P>5. Such further and other relief as this Honourable Court may deem just.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2 LABEL="Part"><N>2:</N><TI>FACTUAL BASIS</TI>
<P>1. These proceedings concern allegations in respect of the provision of services by the plaintiff, NGC Management Ltd., NGC Constructors Ltd. (&ldquo;NGC&rdquo;), in connection with the construction of a commercial building and related improvements to the lands owned by the defendant, Lengara Ventures Inc., now Walker Group Ventures Inc. (&ldquo;Lengara&rdquo;), claims of liens, and the execution of a false statutory declaration.</P>
<P>2. NGC commenced these proceedings on April 19, 2010.</P>
<P>3. Security for NGC's claims was paid into Court by Lengara in August 2010, and a letter of credit was deposited with the Registrar, in substitution, in January 2011, pursuant to orders of this Court.</P>
<P>4. On July 6, 2012, Mr. Justice Keileher, on hearing the application of Lengara, among other things, ordered NGC to post security for costs in the amount of $20,000 and stayed the action until security was posted.</P>
<P>5. On July 6, 2017, Master Muir heard the defendant's application to dismiss the plaintiff's claim for want of prosecution, for an order that posted security be released, and for costs (the &ldquo;Application to Dismiss&rdquo;).</P>
<P>6. On July 24, 2017, Master Muir's Reasons for Judgment were released. Master Muir dismissed the plaintiff's claim and ordered that the letter of credit in the amount of $323,585.35, posted as security for release of the lien registered by the plaintiff against the title to lands owned by the defendant, be returned to the issuing bank, Canadian Western Bank, and allowed the defendant its costs, payable forthwith.</P>
<P>7. NGC filed a Notice of Appeal on August 4, 2017, setting down the hearing of the appeal for October 24, 2017, with an estimate of 2 hours.</P>
<P>8. Counsel for NGC had previously communicated that 1<TEXTFRAC>1/2</TEXTFRAC> days were required for the hearing of its appeal and counsel for Lengara estimated 2 days; the parties have yet to secure dates for the proper hearing of the appeal.</P>
<P>9. NGC served its Notice of Appeal by facsimile on August 11, 2017, at 4:03PM, advising its Statement of Argument would follow on August 14, 2107.</P>
<P>10. Counsel for Lengara has no record of service of NGC's Statement of Argument, on August 14, 2017, or at all.</P>
<P>11. Counsel for Lengara wrote to counsel for NGC on August 20 and September 11, 2017, concerning NGC's outstanding Statement of Argument and NGC's intentions regarding its appeal, as well concerning the orders of Master Muir, Master Dick and Master Scarth, prepared and sent for approval by counsel for NGC.</P>
<P>12. There has been no response by or on behalf of NGC to the correspondence from counsel for Lengara dated August 29 or September 11, 2017.</P>
<P>13. NGC has not complied with the Standard Direction for Appeals from Decisions of Masters, Registrars or Special Referees pursuant to Civil Rule 23-6(8) and Family Rule 22-7(8), PD-54.</P>
<P>14. No explanation has been offered by or on behalf of NGC for its continuing refusal and/or neglect to approve the terms of the orders of Master Muir made July 24, 2017, Master Dick made April 5, 2017, or Master Scarth made December 14, 2016.</P>
<P>15. No explanation has been offered by or on behalf of NGC for its refusal and/or neglect to comply with the Standard Direction for Appeals from Decisions of Masters, Registrars or Special Referees pursuant to Civil Rule 23-6(8) and Family Rule 22-7(8), PD-54.</P>
<P>16. NGC has a history of inaction, delays and non-compliance in these proceedings.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2 LABEL="Part"><N>3:</N><TI>LEGAL BASIS</TI>
<P>1. Supreme Court Civil Rules, 1-3, 13-1, 14-1, 22-7, and 23-6, and the inherent jurisdiction of the Court.</P>
<P>2. Standard Direction for Appeals from Decisions of Masters, Registrars or Special Referees pursuant to Civil Rule 23-6(8) and Family Rule 22-7(8), PD-54.</P>
<P>3. There are a number of authorities from our Court of Appeal which have set out the applicable principles to be considered when exercising discretion on an application to strike a party's pleading, and which have been applied, each case based on its particular facts and discussing relevant factors, including the following:
<P1>a. the party at fault bears the onus of proving a lawful excuse for the non - compliance or non-observance;</P1>
<P1>b. a lawful excuse is one which, in the discretion of the judge acting judicially, is worthy of acceptance; and</P1>
<P1>c. fundamental failures, such as the failure to make appropriate disclosure of documents or records, must be treated as a serious default.</P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>612797 B.C. Ltd. v. Ferguson</SOC><CITE>2009 BCCA 404</CITE></CASEREF></P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Schwarzinger v. Bramwell</SOC><CITE>2011 BCSC 304</CITE></CASEREF></P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Balaj v. Xiaogang</SOC><CITE>2012 BCSC 231</CITE></CASEREF></P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Breberin v. Santos</SOC><CITE>2013 BCSC 560</CITE></CASEREF></P1></P>
<P>4. There is no doubt that NGC has not complied with the Standard Direction for Appeals from Decisions of Masters, Registrars or Special Referees pursuant to Civil Rule 23-6(8) and Family Rule 22-7(8), PD-54. The only question is whether NGC has a lawful excuse and, if there is not, what the sanction should be.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2 LABEL="Part"><N>4:</N><TI>MATERIAL TO BE RELIED ON</TI>
<P>5. Reasons for Judgment of Master Muir dated July 24, 2017;</P>
<P>6. Affidavit #1 of Claudine Aguillon made October 5, 2016;</P>
<P>7. Affidavit #3 of Claudine Aguillon made October 12, 2017; and</P>
<P>8. the pleadings and proceedings filed herein.</P>
<P>The Applicant estimates that the application will take <UNDER>30 minutes</UNDER>.</P>
