<BLOCK1><TI><UNDER>APPLICATION RESPONSE</UNDER></TI>
<P><BOLD>Application response of:</BOLD> NGC Management Ltd. (the &ldquo;application respondent&rdquo;)</P>
<P>THIS IS A RESPONSE TO the notice of application of Lengara Ventures Inc., filed 12/Oct/2017.</P>
<BLOCK2 LABEL="Part"><N>1:</N><TI>ORDERS CONSENTED TO</TI>
<P>The application respondent consents to the granting of none of the orders set out in Part 1 of the notice of application.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2 LABEL="Part"><N>2:</N><TI>ORDERS OPPOSED</TI>
<P>The application respondent opposes the granting of orders set out in paragraphs 1, 3, and 4 of Part 1 of the notice of application.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2 LABEL="Part"><N>3:</N><TI>ORDERS ON WHICH NO POSITION IS TAKEN</TI>
<P>The application respondent takes no position on the granting of the order set out in paragraphs 2 and 5 of Part 1 of the notice of application.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2 LABEL="Part"><N>4:</N><TI>FACTUAL BASIS</TI>
<P>1. At all material times, the application respondent has intended to appeal the decision of Master Muir dated July 24, 2017.</P>
<P>2. A Notice of Appeal was filed on August 4, 2017 on behalf of the application respondent.</P>
<P>3. Through no fault of the application respondent, the application respondent has not yet served its Statement of Argument as counsel for the application respondent has been ill and unable attend to the matter as a result of illness.</P>
<P>4. Counsel for the applicant has advised that he is unavailable for the hearing of the appeal until February 2018.</P>
<P>5. The application respondent is ready, willing, and able to prosecute its appeal in February 2018 in accordance with the applicant's availability. The application respondent therefore submits that there is no prejudice to proceeding with the hearing of the appeal in February 2018 as initially contemplated by the parties.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2 LABEL="Part"><N>5:</N><TI>LEGAL BASIS</TI>
<BLOCK3><TI><UNDER>No Failure to Comply with a Direction</UNDER></TI>
<P>6. Rule 22-7(2) states that a proceeding may be set aside, wholly or in part, based on a party's failure to comply with the <EM>Supreme Court Civil Rules</EM>.</P>
<P>7. Rule 22-7(6) states &ldquo;if a person, without lawful excuse, refuses or neglects to comply with a direction of the court, the court may make an order [to dismiss the proceeding pursuant to Rule 22-7(5)(f)].&rdquo;</P>
<P>8. A practice direction is not a direction of the court. A direction of the court is an order of the court.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Breberin v. Santos</SOC><CITE>2013 BCSC 560</CITE><PARANUM>54</PARANUM></CASEREF></P1></P>
<P>9. A practice direction does not have the same force and effect as legislation, regulations, or court order. It is an informational statement published for the guidance and assistance of registry staff.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>R v Sharpe</SOC><CITE>1999 BCCA 668</CITE><PARANUM>12</PARANUM></CASEREF></P1></P>
<P>10. This interpretation is consistent with the court's reluctance to dismiss a proceeding, and that dismissal &ldquo;is a blunt tool, to be used sparingly&rdquo;.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>House of Sga'nisim v. Canada (Attorney General)</SOC><CITE>2007 BCCA 483</CITE></CASEREF></P1></P>
<P>11. If the legislature had intended to give the time limits imposed by Practice Direction 54 the force of law, the time limits would have been expressly set out in the <EM>Supreme Court Civil Rules</EM>.</P>
<P>12. If the legislature had intended that Rule 22-7 would apply to practice directions, this would have been expressly set out in the <EM>Supreme Court Civil Rules</EM>.</P>
<P>13. Striking a pleading for non-compliance for a reason not contemplated in the <EM>Supreme Court Civil Rules</EM> is a draconian remedy. It is a blunt tool to be used sparingly and in only the most egregious of cases because it deprives the litigants of a trial on the evidence.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Homer Estate v. Eurocopter S.A.</SOC><CITE>2003 BCCA 229</CITE></CASEREF></P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>House of Sga'nisim v. Canada (Attorney General)</SOC><CITE>2007 BCCA 483</CITE></CASEREF></P1></P>
<P>14. Moreover, a dismissal order should not be granted on a first application for relief arising from procedural delay, even intentional delay. Injustice would result from such a course of action. Lesser sanctions ought to be considered where any are available and appropriate.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Breberin v. Santos</SOC><CITE>2013 BCSC 560</CITE><PARANUM>58&ndash;60</PARANUM></CASEREF></P1></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI><UNDER>There is No Wilful or Intentional Delay</UNDER></TI>
<P>15. Moreover, and in the alternative, even if the application respondent failed to comply with the practice direction, &ldquo;the absence of a lawful excuse is only a necessary precondition to exercise the powers; it does not compel the exercise of the powers, as there is a residual discretion to make or not make the orders sought.&rdquo;
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Kondori v. New Country Appliances Inc.</SOC><CITE>2017 BCCA 164</CITE></CASEREF></P1></P>
<P>16. The court may consider other factors such as prejudice to the applicant, prejudice to the application respondent, the draconian nature of the remedy, and the seriousness of the allegations made in the proceeding.</P>
<P>17. At all material times, the application respondent intended to prosecute its appeal.</P>
<P>18. Through no fault of the application respondent, counsel for the application respondent has been ill and unable to finalise and serve the Statement of Argument.</P>
<P>19. The inability of counsel to carry out finalize and provide the Statement of Argument does not constitute refusal or neglect by the party to prosecute its claim. The failure was due to counsel's medical issues and own inadvertence. His failure was not by wilful or deliberate neglect on his part. More importantly, the application respondent respectfully submits that the failure to finalize and serve the Statement of Argument was not due to wilful or deliberate neglect on its own part.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI><UNDER>No Prejudice</UNDER></TI>
<P>20. In relation to the subject appeal, the Notice of Appeal was filed on August 4, 2017.</P>
<P>21. Counsel for the application respondent received the transcript of the chambers proceedings on or about September 13, 2017.</P>
<P>22. On September 11, 2017, counsel for the applicant advised that he was unavailable for the hearing of the appeal until February 2018.</P>
<P>23. The application respondent is ready, willing, and able to prosecute its appeal in February 2018 in accordance with the applicant's availability. The application respondent therefore submits that there is no prejudice to proceeding with the hearing of the appeal in February 2018 as initially contemplated by the parties.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI><UNDER>Special Costs are Not Appropriate</UNDER></TI>
<P>24. Special costs are typically awarded as a punitive measure, as opposed to as an indemnity, where the court seeks to disassociate itself from the conduct of a party to the litigation.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Garcia v. Crestbrook Forest Industries Ltd.</SOC><CITE>1994 CanLII 2570</CITE><COURTJUR>BCCA</COURTJUR></CASEREF></P1></P>
<P>25. There is a single standard for the award of special costs and that is where a party's conduct can be characterised as &ldquo;reprehensible&rdquo;. Reprehensible conduct includes, but is not limited to, conduct which is scandalous and outrageous. It also includes milder forms of conduct deserving of reproof or rebuke.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Garcia v. Crestbrook Forest Industries Ltd.</SOC><CITE>1994 CanLII 2570</CITE><COURTJUR>BCCA</COURTJUR></CASEREF></P1></P>
<P>26. The illness of an officer of the court is not reprehensible conduct on behalf of the application respondent which is deserving of punishment.</P></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
