<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="I"><UNDER>AFFIDAVIT</UNDER></TI>
<P>I, Garrett Munroe, Barrister &amp; Solicitor, c/o Munroe &amp; Company, 2207 - 2850 Shaughnessy Street, in the City of Port Coquitlam, in the Province of British Columbia, AFFIRM THAT:</P>
<P>1. I am counsel for the plaintiff, NGC Management Ltd. (&ldquo;NGC&rdquo;), and therefore have personal knowledge of the facts and matters referred to in this affidavit except where the same are stated to be made upon information and belief and, where so stated, I verily believe the same to be true</P>
<P>2. I received the reasons for judgment of Master Muir (the &ldquo;Decision&rdquo;) on July 24, 2017. I understood that at all material times NGC intended to appeal the Decision.</P>
<P>3. At that time shortly after receiving the Decision, our offices ordered a transcript of the chambers hearing and prepared the Notice of Appeal,</P>
<P>4. The Notice of Appeal was filed on August 4, 2017. Attached hereto and marked as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;A&rdquo;</BOLD> is a true copy of the Notice of Appeal.</P>
<P>5. Around the time that the Notice of Appeal was filed, I began to feet unwell. My symptoms at that time included migraines and fatigue as well as pain in my chest, abdomen, and joints. I was unable to concentrate on complex tasks while suffering from these symptoms.</P>
<P>6. I have suffered from similar symptoms for over one year; however the onset of those symptoms and their duration have been intermittent and are often unpredictable. I had expected that the symptoms would subside within a few days and that the symptoms would not have a material impact on my ability to prosecute the appeal. Regrettably, those symptoms did not and have not resolved to this date. While I did not fully recover from the symptoms, the symptoms did, at times, attenuate to a degree that caused me to believe that my recovery was progressing and that I would soon be able to attend to this matter.</P>
<P>7. On August 11, 2017, my offices prepared a letter serving the Notice of Appeal. The letter was signed on my behalf and sent to counsel for the defendant. The letter explained that I intended to deliver NGC's Statement of Argument on August 14, 2017. The letter reflected my expectation that I would recover sufficiently to allow me to draft the Statement of Argument over the weekend. Attached hereto and marked as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;B&rdquo;</BOLD> is a true copy of the said letter.</P>
<P>8. Regrettably, I did not recover that weekend as I had hoped and anticipated. I subsequently took leave from my office from August 23, 2017 until August 28, 2017 to focus on recovery from my health condition.</P>
<P>9. I felt better upon returning to the office on August 28, 2017 although it was still difficult for me to focus on and accomplish complex tasks requiring concentration. I remained hopeful that I would be able to recover from my symptoms within a short period of time. In hindsight, this may have been an unrealistic belief. I had, at the time, believed that I was simply experiencing a more frequent than usual series of symptoms. I viewed them as a cluster of unwelcome and uncomfortable events rather than the precursor to a more serious, persistent problem. At thirty-three years old, I did not expect that I would fall victim to a serious or prolonged illness; the possibility that I was experiencing something serious and with a long duration seemed to be remote.</P>
<P>10. Over the ensuing days and weeks, I became increasingly overwhelmed with attending to work-related correspondence and my files. I experienced several days during which I had significant difficulty concentrating. On several days, I sat in the dark in my office with the hope that I would be able to manage my symptoms. I was unable to attend to my files on those days. On other days, I felt better which allowed me to be marginally productive although my concentration was still impacted. As a result of those better days, I led myself to believe that recovery was continuing and likely imminent.</P>
<P>11. During this period in August 2017, I relied heavily upon my staff. However, I was unable to delegate the task of drafting and serving a Statement of Argument for an appeal because none of the members of my firm has the ability or experience to accomplish this task. I delegated some of the research and preliminary efforts; however I had to apply myself to review, revise, and supplement this rough draft.</P>
<P>12. There were, in August 2017, two other solicitors working in my office: Sarah Grewal and Sarah Lavrisa. Ms. Lavrisa was called to the bar on April 28 of this year and Ms. Grewal was called to the bar on May 31 of this year.</P>
<P>13. Ms. Grewal ceased to be a member of our firm on September 8, 2017. At no point did I consider it to be appropriate or helpful for Ms. Grewal to work on the appeal.</P>
<P>14. Ms. Lavrisa assisted me to the best of her abilities; however it was necessary for me to review, revise, and complete her work product prior to its submission.</P>
<P>15. I anticipated that reviewing the work of others would be feasible as it would reduce the amount and duration of the concentration required; however I found myself to be unable to accomplish this task despite numerous attempts.</P>
<P>16. In hindsight, I should have delegated the task to another solicitor at another firm. However, I was unable to complete this process as the concentration required to summarise and transfer the file were beyond me at this point. It seemed to me that pushing ahead and trying to finish the Statement of Argument was the better and more appropriate route to take.</P>
<P>17. Beginning in or around late August, I found it increasingly difficult to read. I believed that the persistent migraines and fatigue were responsible for this difficulty.</P>
<P>18. Towards the latter half of September, I became increasingly troubled by a frequent sensation that there was something present in my left peripheral vision. This became worse and was accompanied by apparent rapid movement as if something was running quickly to my left. I then began to see infrequent flashes of light and black dots.</P>
<P>19. My visual symptoms worsened with looking at documents with a white or bright background. While I could see and make-out words on a page generally, my vision was such that the words appeared blurry and were obscured by distortions. It is difficult to describe these distortions; however, the experience is similar to reading text by looking through a thin, translucent chainmail that is vibrating rapidly. Further, large areas of the page seemed to be divided into circles that have an orange hue and glow with varying intensity. These symptoms are ongoing.</P>
<P>20. While it was and is possible for me to read, <BOLD>I</BOLD> do so with great difficulty, poor accuracy, and low speed. I also experienced aggravation of symptoms, including migraine headaches when I attempt to read or to write for extended periods beyond 15 minutes. As a result, I began to take my health extremely seriously and this became my primary focus.</P>
<P>21. I understand that counsel for the defendant sent correspondence to my office at various points following the filing of the Notice of Appeal. <BOLD>I</BOLD> do not deny that my office received that correspondence. However, as a result of my condition, I was unable to review, understand, and deal with that correspondence in a meaningful way nor was I able to advance the appeal.</P>
<P>22. On or about October 2, 2017, I met with my family doctor, Dr. Leung. He advised me to see an optometrist.</P>
<P>23. On October 5, 2017, I met with Dr. Lloyd Mah, optometrist. He performed a physical examination and retinal imaging. Following his examination, he was concerned that I was experiencing a retinal tear. Attached hereto and marked as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;C&rdquo;</BOLD> is a true copy of Dr. Mah's report.</P>
<P>24. At that time, Dr. Mah referred me to Retina Surgical Associates and his office made an appointment with Dr. Robert Gizicki who was acting as locum for Dr. Leah Wittenberg.</P>
<P>25. On or about October 6, 2017, I met with Dr. Gizicki. There were some issues with dilating my pupils prior to his examination and Dr. Gizicki had trouble conducting a complete examination. Following his examination, Dr. Gizicki ruled out a retinal tear but suspected a posterior vitreous detachment (PVD) in both eyes. Attached hereto and marked as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;D&rdquo;</BOLD> is a true copy of Dr. Gizicki's report.</P>
<P>26. I was very concerned about Dr. Gizicki's diagnosis. Through my own research of PVD, I learned that the illness primarily affects the elderly with approximately half of people aged eighty having experienced a PVD. I am thirty-three years old and, as such, a diagnosis of a PVD in a patient of my age is very rare and concerning.</P>
<P>27. I became increasingly concerned that Dr. Gizicki's diagnosis was incorrect when I did not experience any improvement in my symptoms over the next two weeks. I also experienced physical discomfort which was not resolving. I attempted to schedule an appointment with Dr. Leung; however he was unavailable.</P>
<P>28. Instead, on or about October 20, 2017, I met with Dr. Andrew Cheong. Dr. Cheong practices in the same clinic as Dr. Leung. Dr. Cheong referred me to an optometrist and I attended at the optometrist's office immediately following this appointment. I was advised by the optician that they were unable to provide relief for the physical discomfort or provide any assurances beyond confirming that I was not experiencing a retinal detachment. They referred me back to Retina Surgical Associates and advised me to attend an Emergency Room if my vision deteriorated further over the weekend.</P>
<P>29. At the end of my appointment, Dr. Cheong provided me with a copy of Dr. Mah's report. I noticed that Dr. Mah did not find any vitreous cells in his examination. This appeared to me to possibly contradict Dr. Gizicki's diagnosis of a posterior vitreous detachment.</P>
<P>30. On or about October 23, 2017, I made an appointment with another doctor at Dr. Leung's clinic as Dr. Leung was away. The doctor advised me to schedule another appointment. I hoped to resolve the apparent contradiction between Dr. Mah's report and Dr. Gizicki's diagnosis. The doctor advised me to schedule another appointment with Dr. Leung and to contact my ophthalmologist. At that time, I scheduled the first available appointment with Dr. Leung and booked an appointment with Dr. Wittenberg.</P>
<P>31. On or about October 25, 2017, I met with Dr. Leung. He suspected that my visual symptoms included scintillations caused by persistent migraines and exacerbated by poor sleep. He prescribed amitriptyline to assist with sleep and suppress the migraine symptoms.</P>
<P>32. On or about October 26, 2017, I met with Dr. Wittenberg. Following her examination, she concluded that there was no basis for Dr. Gizicki's diagnosis of a PVD but could not offer a conclusion as to the cause of my symptoms. She did not believe that the visual symptoms were scintillations and suspected instead that the symptoms could be caused by a spasming nerve in the back of my head. I do not yet have Dr. Wittenberg's report. I am advised by her office and I verily believe that she is currently away from the office and has not yet prepared her report.</P>
<P>33. As of November 9, 2017, I do not have a conclusive diagnosis nor do I have satisfactory relief from my symptoms despite the treatment protocols recommended by Drs. Leung and Wittenberg.</P>
<P>34. Until Dr. Wittenberg's examination, I was extremely concerned that I would or could lose my eyesight permanently and that my discomfort would persist indefinitely.</P>
<P>35. While I am now less concerned that I will lose my vision due to a disease of or injury to my eyes, I remain perplexed and incredibly concerned as to the possible cause or causes of my symptoms. I do not understand how or why I am experiencing these symptoms. <BOLD>I</BOLD> remain focussed on and committed to my recovery and obtaining a definitive diagnosis.</P>
